// Generated from bank/*.json — questions grounded in Discover Canada (IRCC).
const QUESTIONS = [{"id":"reg-001","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"Which of the following lists the five regions of Canada?","opts":["Eastern Canada, Western Canada, Northern Canada, Southern Canada, Central Canada","The Maritimes, Ontario, Quebec, the Rockies, the Arctic","The Atlantic Provinces, Central Canada, the Prairie Provinces, the West Coast, the Northern Territories","The Pacific Coast, the Atlantic Coast, the Great Lakes, the Prairies, the Tundra"],"a":2,"expl":"Canada includes five distinct regions: the Atlantic Provinces, Central Canada, the Prairie Provinces, the West Coast and the Northern Territories.","diff":1},{"id":"reg-002","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"What is the capital city of Canada?","opts":["Toronto","Ottawa","Montreal","Vancouver"],"a":1,"expl":"Ottawa, located on the Ottawa River, is the capital of Canada and today is Canada's fourth largest metropolitan area.","diff":1},{"id":"reg-003","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"Who chose Ottawa as the capital of Canada in 1857?","opts":["Queen Victoria","Queen Elizabeth II","Sir John A. Macdonald","King George V"],"a":0,"expl":"Ottawa was chosen as the capital in 1857 by Queen Victoria, the great-great-grandmother of Queen Elizabeth II.","diff":2},{"id":"reg-004","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"How many provinces and territories does Canada have?","opts":["Nine provinces and four territories","Twelve provinces and one territory","Ten provinces and two territories","Ten provinces and three territories"],"a":3,"expl":"Canada has ten provinces and three territories, and each has its own capital city.","diff":1},{"id":"reg-005","chapter":10,"type":"tf","q":"Canada has a population of about 60 million people.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"False. The guide states Canada has a population of about 34 million people.","diff":1},{"id":"reg-006","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"What is the capital of Alberta?","opts":["Calgary","Edmonton","Banff","Regina"],"a":1,"expl":"Edmonton is the capital city of Alberta. You should know the capital of your province as well as that of Canada.","diff":1},{"id":"reg-007","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"Which provinces are known as the Prairie Provinces?","opts":["Manitoba, Saskatchewan and Alberta","Alberta, British Columbia and Saskatchewan","Manitoba, Ontario and Saskatchewan","Saskatchewan, Alberta and Yukon"],"a":0,"expl":"Manitoba, Saskatchewan and Alberta are the Prairie Provinces, rich in energy resources and some of the most fertile farmland in the world.","diff":1},{"id":"reg-008","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"Which is the most populous Prairie province?","opts":["Saskatchewan","Manitoba","Alberta","British Columbia"],"a":2,"expl":"Alberta is the most populous Prairie province. (British Columbia is not a Prairie province.)","diff":2},{"id":"reg-009","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"After whom were the province of Alberta and the world-famous Lake Louise named?","opts":["Queen Victoria","Princess Margaret, daughter of King George VI","Queen Elizabeth I","Princess Louise Caroline Alberta"],"a":3,"expl":"Both Alberta and Lake Louise were named after Princess Louise Caroline Alberta, the fourth daughter of Queen Victoria.","diff":3},{"id":"reg-010","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"Which province is the largest producer of oil and gas in Canada?","opts":["Alberta","Saskatchewan","Newfoundland and Labrador","British Columbia"],"a":0,"expl":"Alberta is the largest producer of oil and gas, and the oil sands in the north are being developed as a major energy source.","diff":1},{"id":"reg-011","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"In what year was Banff National Park established?","opts":["1867","1885","1905","1999"],"a":1,"expl":"Alberta has five national parks, including Banff National Park, established in 1885.","diff":3},{"id":"reg-012","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"How many national parks does Alberta have?","opts":["Three","Four","Five","Seven"],"a":2,"expl":"Alberta has five national parks, including Banff National Park.","diff":3},{"id":"reg-013","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"Where is the world-famous Lake Louise located?","opts":["The Badlands","The Canadian Shield","The Appalachian Range","The Rocky Mountains"],"a":3,"expl":"Lake Louise is located in the Rocky Mountains in Alberta.","diff":2},{"id":"reg-014","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"What are Alberta's rugged Badlands known for?","opts":["Some of the world's richest dinosaur fossil deposits","The world's largest gold mines","Canada's biggest hydro-electric dams","The world's highest tides"],"a":0,"expl":"The rugged Badlands house some of the world's richest deposits of prehistoric fossils and dinosaur finds.","diff":2},{"id":"reg-015","chapter":10,"type":"tf","q":"Alberta is renowned for its vast cattle ranches, which help make Canada one of the world's major beef producers.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"True. Alberta is renowned for agriculture, especially the vast cattle ranches that make Canada one of the world's major beef producers.","diff":1},{"id":"reg-016","chapter":10,"type":"tf","q":"Alberta's oil sands are located in the southern part of the province.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"False. The oil sands in the north of Alberta are being developed as a major energy source.","diff":2},{"id":"reg-017","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"How does the guide describe the climate of the Prairie Provinces?","opts":["Temperate, with warm airstreams from the Pacific","Mostly dry, with cold winters and hot summers","Cool winters and cool humid summers","Long cold winters and short cool summers"],"a":1,"expl":"The Prairie region is mostly dry, with cold winters and hot summers. (The temperate climate describes the B.C. coast; cool winters and humid summers describe Atlantic Canada; long cold winters describe the North.)","diff":2},{"id":"reg-018","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"What is the capital of Saskatchewan?","opts":["Saskatoon","Winnipeg","Regina","Moose Jaw"],"a":2,"expl":"Regina is the capital of Saskatchewan. Saskatoon is the province's largest city.","diff":1},{"id":"reg-019","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"Regina is home to which national institution?","opts":["The headquarters of the navy's Pacific fleet","Canada's largest naval base","The Geological Survey of Canada","The training academy of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police"],"a":3,"expl":"Regina, the capital of Saskatchewan, is home to the training academy of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police.","diff":2},{"id":"reg-020","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"Which province was once known as the \"breadbasket of the world\" and the \"wheat province\"?","opts":["Saskatchewan","Manitoba","Ontario","Alberta"],"a":0,"expl":"Saskatchewan was once known as the \"breadbasket of the world\" and the \"wheat province\"; it has 40% of the arable land in Canada and is the country's largest producer of grains and oilseeds.","diff":1},{"id":"reg-021","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"Saskatchewan boasts the world's richest deposits of which two resources?","opts":["Gold and silver","Uranium and potash","Diamonds and zinc","Coal and copper"],"a":1,"expl":"Saskatchewan boasts the world's richest deposits of uranium and potash, which is used in fertilizer.","diff":3},{"id":"reg-022","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"What is the capital of Manitoba?","opts":["Brandon","Regina","St. Boniface","Winnipeg"],"a":3,"expl":"Winnipeg is the capital and most populous city of Manitoba. St. Boniface is Winnipeg's French Quarter.","diff":1},{"id":"reg-023","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"Portage and Main, the most famous street intersection in Canada, is found in which city?","opts":["Toronto","Calgary","Winnipeg","Edmonton"],"a":2,"expl":"Winnipeg's Exchange District includes Portage and Main, the most famous street intersection in Canada.","diff":3},{"id":"reg-024","chapter":10,"type":"tf","q":"Manitoba has the largest Aboriginal population of any province, at over 15 per cent.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"True. Manitoba has the largest Aboriginal population of any province, at over 15%, and is also an important centre of Ukrainian culture.","diff":2},{"id":"reg-025","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"Which provinces make up the Atlantic Provinces?","opts":["Newfoundland and Labrador, Prince Edward Island, Nova Scotia and New Brunswick","Quebec, New Brunswick, Nova Scotia and Prince Edward Island","Nova Scotia, New Brunswick, Ontario and Newfoundland and Labrador","Prince Edward Island, Nova Scotia, Quebec and Newfoundland and Labrador"],"a":0,"expl":"The four Atlantic Provinces are Newfoundland and Labrador, Prince Edward Island, Nova Scotia and New Brunswick. Quebec and Ontario form Central Canada.","diff":1},{"id":"reg-026","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"What is the capital of Nova Scotia?","opts":["Fredericton","Halifax","Charlottetown","Sydney"],"a":1,"expl":"Halifax is the capital of Nova Scotia, Canada's largest east coast port and home to Canada's largest naval base. Fredericton is New Brunswick's capital and Charlottetown is Prince Edward Island's.","diff":1},{"id":"reg-027","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"The Bay of Fundy in Nova Scotia is known for what?","opts":["The world's longest bridge","Canada's busiest port","The world's highest tides","The most easterly point in North America"],"a":2,"expl":"Nova Scotia is known for the world's highest tides in the Bay of Fundy.","diff":2},{"id":"reg-029","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"Which province is the smallest in Canada and known as the birthplace of Confederation?","opts":["Prince Edward Island","Nova Scotia","New Brunswick","Manitoba"],"a":0,"expl":"Prince Edward Island (P.E.I.) is the smallest province, known for its beaches, red soil and potatoes, and is the birthplace of Confederation. It is connected to the mainland by the Confederation Bridge.","diff":1},{"id":"reg-030","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"Mount Logan, the highest mountain in Canada, is located in which province or territory?","opts":["British Columbia","Yukon","Alberta","Northwest Territories"],"a":1,"expl":"Mount Logan, located in the Yukon, is the highest mountain in Canada. It is named after Sir William Logan, a world-famous geologist.","diff":3},{"id":"reg-031","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"Which province is the most easterly point in North America and has its own time zone?","opts":["Nova Scotia","Prince Edward Island","Newfoundland and Labrador","New Brunswick"],"a":2,"expl":"Newfoundland and Labrador is the most easterly point in North America, has its own time zone, and was the oldest colony of the British Empire.","diff":2},{"id":"reg-032","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"What is the capital of Newfoundland and Labrador?","opts":["Saint John","Halifax","Corner Brook","St. John's"],"a":3,"expl":"St. John's is the capital of Newfoundland and Labrador. (Saint John is the largest city in New Brunswick.)","diff":1},{"id":"reg-033","chapter":10,"type":"tf","q":"More than half the people in Canada live in cities and towns near the Great Lakes and the St. Lawrence River.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"True. More than half the people in Canada live near the Great Lakes and the St. Lawrence River in southern Quebec and Ontario, known as Central Canada, the industrial and manufacturing heartland.","diff":2},{"id":"reg-034","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"Together, Ontario and Quebec produce what share of all Canadian manufactured goods?","opts":["More than three-quarters","About one-quarter","About half","Nearly one-tenth"],"a":0,"expl":"Together, Ontario and Quebec produce more than three-quarters of all Canadian manufactured goods.","diff":2},{"id":"reg-035","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"Which city is the largest in Canada and the country's main financial centre?","opts":["Montreal","Toronto","Ottawa","Vancouver"],"a":1,"expl":"Toronto is the largest city in Canada and the country's main financial centre. It is also the capital of Ontario.","diff":1},{"id":"reg-036","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"Which province is Canada's largest producer of hydro-electricity?","opts":["Ontario","Manitoba","Quebec","British Columbia"],"a":2,"expl":"Quebec's huge supply of fresh water has made it Canada's largest producer of hydro-electricity. Quebec is also Canada's main producer of pulp and paper.","diff":2},{"id":"reg-037","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"Montreal is the second largest mainly French-speaking city in the world after which city?","opts":["Brussels","Quebec City","Geneva","Paris"],"a":3,"expl":"Montreal, Canada's second largest city, is the second largest mainly French-speaking city in the world after Paris.","diff":3},{"id":"reg-038","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"What is the capital of British Columbia?","opts":["Victoria","Vancouver","Kelowna","Whitehorse"],"a":0,"expl":"Victoria is the capital of British Columbia, a tourist centre and headquarters of the navy's Pacific fleet.","diff":1},{"id":"reg-039","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"What is Canada's largest and busiest port?","opts":["The Port of Halifax","The Port of Vancouver","The Port of Montreal","The Port of Saint John"],"a":1,"expl":"The Port of Vancouver, Canada's largest and busiest, handles billions of dollars in goods traded around the world and is our gateway to the Asia-Pacific.","diff":2},{"id":"reg-040","chapter":10,"type":"tf","q":"About one-half of all the goods produced in British Columbia are forestry products.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"True. About one-half of all goods produced in B.C. are forestry products, including lumber, newsprint, and pulp and paper products - the most valuable forestry industry in Canada.","diff":2},{"id":"reg-041","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"After English, which are the most spoken languages in British Columbia's cities?","opts":["French and German","Spanish and Italian","Chinese and Punjabi","Japanese and Korean"],"a":2,"expl":"British Columbia's large Asian communities have made Chinese and Punjabi the most spoken languages in the cities after English.","diff":3},{"id":"reg-042","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"What does \"Nunavut\" mean in Inuktitut?","opts":["\"Land of the midnight sun\"","\"The frozen north\"","\"Place of many fish\"","\"Our land\""],"a":3,"expl":"Nunavut means \"our land\" in Inuktitut. It was established in 1999 from the eastern part of the Northwest Territories, and its population is about 85% Inuit.","diff":2},{"id":"reg-043","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"What is the capital of the Northwest Territories?","opts":["Yellowknife","Iqaluit","Whitehorse","Dawson City"],"a":0,"expl":"Yellowknife, called the \"diamond capital of North America,\" is the capital of the Northwest Territories. Iqaluit is the capital of Nunavut and Whitehorse is the capital of Yukon.","diff":1},{"id":"reg-044","chapter":10,"type":"tf","q":"The capital of Nunavut is Whitehorse.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"False. The capital of Nunavut is Iqaluit (formerly Frobisher Bay). Whitehorse is the capital of Yukon.","diff":1},{"id":"reg-045","chapter":10,"type":"mc","q":"Why is Canada's North often referred to as the \"Land of the Midnight Sun\"?","opts":["Because the northern lights glow at night","Because at the height of summer, daylight can last up to 24 hours","Because the sun never sets in winter","Because miners worked through the night during the Gold Rush"],"a":1,"expl":"The North is called the \"Land of the Midnight Sun\" because at the height of summer, daylight can last up to 24 hours. In winter, the sun disappears and darkness sets in for three months.","diff":2},{"id":"rights-001","chapter":1,"type":"tf","q":"There is no compulsory military service in Canada.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"The guide states there is no compulsory military service in Canada; serving in the forces is a noble way to contribute and an excellent career choice, but it is voluntary.","diff":1},{"id":"rights-002","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"In what year was the Magna Carta signed in England?","opts":["1199","1215","1867","1982"],"a":1,"expl":"The guide says Canada's 800-year-old tradition of ordered liberty dates back to the signing of the Magna Carta in 1215 in England.","diff":1},{"id":"rights-003","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"The Magna Carta is also known as:","opts":["The Constitution Act","The British North America Act","The Great Charter of Freedoms","The Charter of Rights and Freedoms"],"a":2,"expl":"The guide notes the Magna Carta is also known as the Great Charter of Freedoms.","diff":1},{"id":"rights-004","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"In what year was the Constitution of Canada amended to entrench the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms?","opts":["1867","1905","1931","1982"],"a":3,"expl":"The Constitution of Canada was amended in 1982 to entrench the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms.","diff":1},{"id":"rights-005","chapter":1,"type":"tf","q":"In Canada, men and women are equal under the law.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"The guide states plainly that in Canada, men and women are equal under the law.","diff":1},{"id":"rights-006","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"Which of the following is a responsibility of Canadian citizenship?","opts":["Serving on a jury when called to do so","Owning property in Canada","Belonging to a political party","Serving in the navy, army or air force"],"a":0,"expl":"Serving on a jury is listed among the citizenship responsibilities; when called to do so, you are legally required to serve. Military service is not compulsory in Canada.","diff":1},{"id":"rights-007","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"What is habeas corpus?","opts":["The right to vote in federal elections","The right to challenge unlawful detention by the state","The right to a free education","The right to live and work anywhere in Canada"],"a":1,"expl":"Habeas corpus is the right to challenge unlawful detention by the state, and it comes from English common law.","diff":1},{"id":"rights-008","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"In the Charter, multiculturalism is described as:","opts":["A temporary government program","A policy that applies only in large cities","A fundamental characteristic of the Canadian heritage and identity","A requirement that applies only to newcomers"],"a":2,"expl":"The guide describes multiculturalism as a fundamental characteristic of the Canadian heritage and identity; Canadians work hard to respect pluralism and live in harmony.","diff":1},{"id":"rights-009","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"Under official language rights, which two languages have equal status in Parliament and throughout the government?","opts":["English and Inuktitut","French and English","English and Spanish","French and Cree"],"a":1,"expl":"The guide states that French and English have equal status in Parliament and throughout the government.","diff":1},{"id":"rights-010","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"Under mobility rights, Canadians can:","opts":["Vote in any country's elections","Avoid paying provincial taxes","Claim land anywhere in Canada","Live and work anywhere they choose in Canada"],"a":3,"expl":"Mobility rights mean Canadians can live and work anywhere they choose in Canada, enter and leave the country freely, and apply for a passport.","diff":1},{"id":"rights-011","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"What will you do at the citizenship ceremony?","opts":["Take the Oath of Citizenship and receive your citizenship certificate","Write the citizenship test and receive a passport","Receive a Notice to Appear and pay a fee","Register to vote and receive a social insurance number"],"a":0,"expl":"At the ceremony you take the Oath of Citizenship, sign the oath form, and receive your Canadian Citizenship Certificate.","diff":1},{"id":"rights-012","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"In the Oath of Citizenship, to whom do new citizens pledge to be faithful and bear true allegiance?","opts":["The flag of Canada","The Constitution of Canada","The Queen of Canada, her heirs and successors","The Prime Minister of Canada"],"a":2,"expl":"The oath pledges faithfulness and true allegiance to Her Majesty the Queen of Canada, her heirs and successors; loyalty is professed to a person who represents all Canadians, not to a document, flag or country.","diff":1},{"id":"rights-013","chapter":1,"type":"tf","q":"When called to serve on a jury, you are legally required to serve.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"The guide states that when called to do so, you are legally required to serve on a jury.","diff":1},{"id":"rights-014","chapter":1,"type":"tf","q":"Canada's openness and generosity extend to cultural practices such as forced marriage and other gender-based violence.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"False. The guide says Canada's openness and generosity do not extend to barbaric cultural practices such as spousal abuse, 'honour killings', female genital mutilation, forced marriage or other gender-based violence.","diff":1},{"id":"rights-015","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"Which of the following is one of the fundamental freedoms Canadians enjoy?","opts":["Freedom to own firearms","Freedom from taxation","Freedom of peaceful assembly","Freedom of unlimited travel abroad"],"a":2,"expl":"Freedom of peaceful assembly is one of the fundamental freedoms, along with freedom of conscience and religion, freedom of thought, belief, opinion and expression, and freedom of association.","diff":1},{"id":"rights-016","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"Voting in elections is described in the guide as:","opts":["Optional for citizens over 55","A responsibility that comes with the right to vote","Required only in federal elections","A privilege reserved for those born in Canada"],"a":1,"expl":"The guide says the right to vote comes with a responsibility to vote in federal, provincial or territorial and local elections.","diff":1},{"id":"rights-017","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"Which of the following is NOT listed as a source of Canadian law?","opts":["English common law","The civil code of France","Laws passed by Parliament and the provincial legislatures","The United States Bill of Rights"],"a":3,"expl":"The sources of Canadian law are laws passed by Parliament and the provincial legislatures, English common law, the civil code of France, and the unwritten constitution inherited from Great Britain.","diff":2},{"id":"rights-018","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"From where does habeas corpus come?","opts":["English common law","The civil code of France","The 1982 Charter of Rights and Freedoms","The Citizenship Regulations"],"a":0,"expl":"The guide states that habeas corpus, the right to challenge unlawful detention by the state, comes from English common law.","diff":2},{"id":"rights-019","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"Which list contains only fundamental freedoms identified in the guide?","opts":["Freedom of conscience and religion; freedom of thought, belief, opinion and expression; freedom of peaceful assembly; freedom of association","Freedom of movement; freedom of trade; freedom of property; freedom of contract","Freedom of education; freedom of health care; freedom of housing; freedom of employment","Freedom of information; freedom of the seas; freedom of trade; freedom of worship"],"a":0,"expl":"The four fundamental freedoms are freedom of conscience and religion; freedom of thought, belief, opinion and expression (including speech and press); freedom of peaceful assembly; and freedom of association.","diff":2},{"id":"rights-020","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"Freedom of speech and of the press is included within which fundamental freedom?","opts":["Freedom of association","Freedom of peaceful assembly","Freedom of thought, belief, opinion and expression","Freedom of conscience and religion"],"a":2,"expl":"The guide lists freedom of thought, belief, opinion and expression as including freedom of speech and of the press.","diff":2},{"id":"rights-021","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"What does the Charter say about Aboriginal Peoples' Rights?","opts":["They expired when the Charter was entrenched in 1982","The Charter will not adversely affect any treaty or other rights of Aboriginal peoples","They apply only to First Nations, not to Inuit or Metis","They must be renegotiated every ten years"],"a":1,"expl":"The guide states that the rights guaranteed in the Charter will not adversely affect any treaty or other rights or freedoms of Aboriginal peoples.","diff":2},{"id":"rights-022","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"The guide says Canadians enjoy an '800-year old tradition of ordered liberty' that dates back to:","opts":["Confederation in 1867","The signing of the Magna Carta in 1215","The Quebec Act of 1774","The Constitution Act of 1982"],"a":1,"expl":"The sources of Canadian law together secure an 800-year-old tradition of ordered liberty dating back to the signing of the Magna Carta in 1215 in England.","diff":2},{"id":"rights-023","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"Besides the regular Canadian Forces, which of the following does the guide mention as a way to help protect your community?","opts":["Serving in the Coast Guard, a police force or a fire department","Paying extra income tax","Joining a federal political party","Working for a multinational corporation"],"a":0,"expl":"The guide says you may also serve in the Coast Guard or in emergency services in your community, such as a police force or fire department.","diff":2},{"id":"rights-024","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"According to the guide, what can young people gain by getting involved in the cadets?","opts":["A guaranteed career in the regular forces","Exemption from the citizenship test","Free university tuition","Discipline, responsibility and skills"],"a":3,"expl":"The guide says young people can learn discipline, responsibility and skills by getting involved in the cadets.","diff":2},{"id":"rights-025","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"In the Oath of Citizenship, what do new citizens promise to faithfully observe?","opts":["The traditions of the founding peoples","The decisions of the Prime Minister","The laws of Canada","The rulings of the Supreme Court"],"a":2,"expl":"In the oath, new citizens promise to faithfully observe the laws of Canada and fulfil their duties as a Canadian citizen.","diff":2},{"id":"rights-026","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"According to the guide, in Canada we profess our loyalty to:","opts":["A document, such as a constitution","A banner, such as a flag","A geopolitical entity, such as a country","A person who represents all Canadians, the Sovereign"],"a":3,"expl":"The guide explains that in Canada we profess loyalty to a person who represents all Canadians — the Sovereign (Queen or King) — and not to a document, a flag or a country.","diff":2},{"id":"rights-027","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"The responsibility of protecting and enjoying our heritage and environment includes:","opts":["Avoiding waste and pollution and protecting Canada's natural heritage","Donating to environmental charities each year","Purchasing only Canadian-made goods","Joining a provincial conservation service"],"a":0,"expl":"The guide says every citizen has a role to play in avoiding waste and pollution while protecting Canada's natural, cultural and architectural heritage for future generations.","diff":2},{"id":"rights-028","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"Which of the following is given in the guide as an example of helping others in the community?","opts":["Paying taxes on time","Volunteering at a food bank or other charity","Serving in the air reserves","Running for elected office"],"a":1,"expl":"Examples of helping others include helping people in need, assisting at your child's school, volunteering at a food bank or other charity, and encouraging newcomers to integrate.","diff":2},{"id":"rights-029","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"What does the rule of law mean, according to the guide?","opts":["Judges make all of Canada's laws","Only the federal government can pass laws","Individuals and governments are regulated by laws, not arbitrary actions","Police forces have final authority over the courts"],"a":2,"expl":"One of Canada's founding principles is the rule of law: individuals and governments are regulated by laws and not by arbitrary actions, and no person or group is above the law.","diff":2},{"id":"rights-030","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"Which of the following is an example of taking responsibility for oneself and one's family?","opts":["Voting in every election","Serving on a jury","Volunteering regularly at a local charity","Getting a job and taking care of one's family"],"a":3,"expl":"The guide says getting a job, taking care of one's family and working hard in keeping with one's abilities are important Canadian values, and work contributes to personal dignity, self-respect and Canada's prosperity.","diff":2},{"id":"rights-031","chapter":1,"type":"tf","q":"The right to vote comes with a responsibility to vote in federal, provincial or territorial and local elections.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"The guide lists voting in elections as a citizenship responsibility at the federal, provincial or territorial and local levels.","diff":2},{"id":"rights-032","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"According to the guide, how does Canada respond to 'barbaric cultural practices' such as spousal abuse, 'honour killings', female genital mutilation or forced marriage?","opts":["They are tolerated as part of Canada's openness and generosity","They are handled only by community leaders","Offenders are required to take citizenship classes","Those guilty of these crimes are severely punished under Canada's criminal laws"],"a":3,"expl":"The guide states that those guilty of these crimes are severely punished under Canada's criminal laws.","diff":2},{"id":"rights-033","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"With which words does the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms begin?","opts":["'We the people of Canada, in order to form a more perfect union...'","'Whereas Canada is founded upon principles that recognize the supremacy of God and the rule of law'","'Peace, order and good government...'","'Canada is a free and democratic society...'"],"a":1,"expl":"The Charter begins with the words 'Whereas Canada is founded upon principles that recognize the supremacy of God and the rule of law.'","diff":3},{"id":"rights-034","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"According to the guide, the Charter's opening phrase underlines the importance of:","opts":["Parliamentary supremacy and federalism","The separation of church and state","Religious traditions and the dignity and worth of the human person","Economic prosperity and free trade"],"a":2,"expl":"The guide says this phrase underlines the importance of religious traditions to Canadian society and the dignity and worth of the human person.","diff":3},{"id":"rights-035","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"According to the guide, Canadians' rights and responsibilities come to us from our history, are secured by Canadian law, and reflect:","opts":["Our shared traditions, identity and values","International human rights treaties","The will of the federal government","The customs of the British Empire alone"],"a":0,"expl":"The guide states that rights and responsibilities come from our history, are secured by Canadian law, and reflect our shared traditions, identity and values.","diff":3},{"id":"rights-036","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"Which of the following is included in mobility rights?","opts":["The right to free public transit","The right to dual citizenship","The right to a government job in any province","The right to enter and leave Canada freely and to apply for a passport"],"a":3,"expl":"Mobility rights include living and working anywhere in Canada, entering and leaving the country freely, and applying for a passport.","diff":3},{"id":"rights-037","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"From which country did Canada inherit its unwritten constitution, one of the sources of Canadian law?","opts":["France","The United States","Great Britain","The Netherlands"],"a":2,"expl":"The guide lists the unwritten constitution that Canada inherited from Great Britain among the sources of Canadian law.","diff":3},{"id":"rights-038","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"Why is serving on a jury described as a privilege that makes the justice system work?","opts":["Because jurors are paid generously for their service","Because the justice system depends on impartial juries made up of citizens","Because juries can overturn laws passed by Parliament","Because jury service replaces the need for judges"],"a":1,"expl":"The guide says serving on a jury is a privilege that makes the justice system work, as it depends on impartial juries made up of citizens.","diff":3},{"id":"rights-039","chapter":1,"type":"mc","q":"In the Oath of Citizenship, the Constitution is described as recognizing and affirming the Aboriginal and treaty rights of:","opts":["First Nations, Inuit and Metis peoples","Status Indians only","First Nations and Acadians","All Indigenous peoples of North America"],"a":0,"expl":"The oath includes observing the laws of Canada, including the Constitution, which recognizes and affirms the Aboriginal and treaty rights of First Nations, Inuit and Metis peoples.","diff":3},{"id":"rights-040","chapter":1,"type":"tf","q":"Habeas corpus, the right to challenge unlawful detention, was created by the 1982 Charter of Rights and Freedoms.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"False. Habeas corpus comes from English common law, not from the 1982 Charter.","diff":3},{"id":"who-001","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"Who are the three founding peoples of Canada?","opts":["English, Irish and Scottish","Aboriginal, American and British","Aboriginal, French and British","French, British and Dutch"],"a":2,"expl":"The guide states that to understand what it means to be Canadian, it is important to know about our three founding peoples: Aboriginal, French and British.","diff":1},{"id":"who-002","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"Today, the term Aboriginal peoples refers to which three distinct groups?","opts":["First Nations, Inuit and Metis","Cree, Huron and Sioux","Indian, Eskimo and Acadian","First Nations, Dene and Mohawk"],"a":0,"expl":"The guide says the term Aboriginal peoples refers to three distinct groups: Indian (First Nations), Inuit and Metis.","diff":1},{"id":"who-003","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"What does the word \"Inuit\" mean in the Inuktitut language?","opts":["The hunters","The land","The North","The people"],"a":3,"expl":"Inuit means \"the people\" in the Inuktitut language.","diff":1},{"id":"who-004","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"Where do the majority of Metis people live?","opts":["The Atlantic provinces","The Prairie provinces","The Arctic territories","Quebec"],"a":1,"expl":"The Metis are a distinct people of mixed Aboriginal and European ancestry, the majority of whom live in the Prairie provinces.","diff":1},{"id":"who-005","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"What is the name of the dialect spoken by the Metis?","opts":["Michif","Inuktitut","Cree","Mohawk"],"a":0,"expl":"The Metis come from both French- and English-speaking backgrounds and speak their own dialect, Michif.","diff":2},{"id":"who-006","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"Which is the only officially bilingual province in Canada?","opts":["Quebec","Manitoba","New Brunswick","Ontario"],"a":2,"expl":"The guide states that New Brunswick is the only officially bilingual province.","diff":1},{"id":"who-007","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"What are the two official languages of Canada?","opts":["English and Inuktitut","English and French","French and Michif","English and Chinese"],"a":1,"expl":"English and French are the country's official languages, and the federal government is required by law to provide services in both.","diff":1},{"id":"who-008","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"According to the guide, how many Anglophones (people who speak English as a first language) are there in Canada?","opts":["7 million","25 million","12 million","18 million"],"a":3,"expl":"The guide says there are 18 million Anglophones and seven million Francophones.","diff":2},{"id":"who-009","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"How many Francophones (people who speak French as their first language) live in Canada, according to the guide?","opts":["Seven million","One million","Eighteen million","Three million"],"a":0,"expl":"There are seven million Francophones; the majority live in Quebec, with one million in Ontario, New Brunswick and Manitoba.","diff":2},{"id":"who-010","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"The Acadians are the descendants of which group?","opts":["British Loyalists who fled the American Revolution","French colonists who began settling in the Maritime provinces in 1604","Irish settlers who arrived in the 1800s","Aboriginal peoples of the Atlantic coast"],"a":1,"expl":"The Acadians are the descendants of French colonists who began settling in what are now the Maritime provinces in 1604.","diff":1},{"id":"who-011","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"What event is known as the \"Great Upheaval\"?","opts":["The migration of Aboriginal ancestors from Asia","The Quebec sovereignty referendum","The placing of Aboriginal children in residential schools","The deportation of more than two-thirds of the Acadians between 1755 and 1763"],"a":3,"expl":"Between 1755 and 1763, during the war between Britain and France, more than two-thirds of the Acadians were deported from their homeland, an ordeal known as the \"Great Upheaval.\"","diff":2},{"id":"who-012","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"What did the House of Commons recognize in 2006?","opts":["That New Brunswick is officially bilingual","That French is an official language","That the Quebecois form a nation within a united Canada","That the Acadians deserved an apology for the Great Upheaval"],"a":2,"expl":"The House of Commons recognized in 2006 that the Quebecois form a nation within a united Canada.","diff":2},{"id":"who-013","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"How were the territorial rights of Aboriginal peoples first guaranteed?","opts":["Through the Royal Proclamation of 1763 by King George III","Through the British North America Act of 1867","Through a House of Commons motion in 2006","Through the residential schools system"],"a":0,"expl":"Territorial rights were first guaranteed through the Royal Proclamation of 1763 by King George III, which established the basis for negotiating treaties.","diff":2},{"id":"who-014","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"What did the federal government do in 2008 regarding residential schools?","opts":["Opened the first residential school","Formally apologized to the former students","Transferred the schools to the provinces","Placed Aboriginal children in residential schools"],"a":1,"expl":"In 2008, Ottawa formally apologized to the former students of residential schools.","diff":2},{"id":"who-015","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"Canada is the only country in North America that is a:","opts":["Republic","Federation","Constitutional monarchy","Direct democracy"],"a":2,"expl":"The guide states that Canada is the only constitutional monarchy in North America.","diff":1},{"id":"who-016","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"The phrase \"Peace, Order and Good Government\" comes from which document?","opts":["The Royal Proclamation of 1763","The Quebec Act of 1774","The Official Languages Act","The British North America Act of 1867"],"a":3,"expl":"\"Peace, Order and Good Government\" is a key phrase in Canada's original constitutional document of 1867, the British North America Act.","diff":2},{"id":"who-017","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"According to the guide, about what percentage of Aboriginal people are First Nations?","opts":["65%","30%","50%","4%"],"a":0,"expl":"About 65% of Aboriginal people are First Nations, while 30% are Metis and 4% Inuit.","diff":3},{"id":"who-018","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"About half of First Nations people live on reserve land in approximately how many communities?","opts":["100","600","1,200","60"],"a":1,"expl":"Today, about half of First Nations people live on reserve land in about 600 communities, while the other half live off-reserve, mainly in urban centres.","diff":3},{"id":"who-019","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"Since the 1970s, most immigrants to Canada have come from which part of the world?","opts":["European countries","African countries","Asian countries","South American countries"],"a":2,"expl":"The guide states that since the 1970s, most immigrants have come from Asian countries.","diff":1},{"id":"who-020","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"What is the largest religious affiliation in Canada?","opts":["Catholic","Protestant","Muslim","Jewish"],"a":0,"expl":"The largest religious affiliation is Catholic, followed by various Protestant churches.","diff":1},{"id":"who-021","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"In Vancouver, what percentage of the population speaks Chinese languages at home?","opts":["7%","25%","2%","13%"],"a":3,"expl":"In Vancouver, 13% of the population speak Chinese languages at home; in Toronto, the number is 7%.","diff":3},{"id":"who-022","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"The basic way of life in English-speaking areas of Canada was established by hundreds of thousands of settlers from which groups?","opts":["German, Italian and Dutch","English, Welsh, Scottish and Irish","Ukrainian, Polish and Scandinavian","French, Acadian and Metis"],"a":1,"expl":"The basic way of life in English-speaking areas was established by hundreds of thousands of English, Welsh, Scottish and Irish settlers, soldiers and migrants from the 1600s to the 20th century.","diff":2},{"id":"who-023","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"Who was John Buchan, the 1st Baron Tweedsmuir?","opts":["The first French-speaking Prime Minister","A famous Haida artist","A popular Governor General of Canada (1935-40)","The founder of the Hudson's Bay Company"],"a":2,"expl":"John Buchan, the 1st Baron Tweedsmuir, was a popular Governor General of Canada from 1935 to 1940 who said immigrant groups \"should retain their individuality and each make its contribution to the national character.\"","diff":3},{"id":"who-024","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"In becoming Canadian, newcomers are expected to embrace:","opts":["A single national language","Their former country's legal traditions","Membership in a specific religion","Democratic principles such as the rule of law"],"a":3,"expl":"The guide states that in becoming Canadian, newcomers are expected to embrace democratic principles such as the rule of law.","diff":2},{"id":"who-025","chapter":2,"type":"mc","q":"Most Quebecers are descendants of approximately how many French settlers from the 1600s and 1700s?","opts":["8,500","40,000","100,000","3,000"],"a":0,"expl":"Most Quebecers are descendants of 8,500 French settlers from the 1600s and 1700s and maintain a unique identity, culture and language.","diff":3},{"id":"who-026","chapter":2,"type":"tf","q":"New Brunswick is the only officially bilingual province in Canada.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"True. The guide states that New Brunswick is the only officially bilingual province.","diff":1},{"id":"who-027","chapter":2,"type":"tf","q":"The majority of Canadians were born outside of Canada.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"False. The majority of Canadians were born in this country, and this has been true since the 1800s, although Canada is often referred to as a land of immigrants.","diff":1},{"id":"who-028","chapter":2,"type":"tf","q":"The Inuit live in small, scattered communities across the Arctic.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"True. The Inuit live in small, scattered communities across the Arctic, and their knowledge of the land, sea and wildlife enabled them to adapt to one of the harshest environments on earth.","diff":2},{"id":"who-029","chapter":2,"type":"tf","q":"The majority of Francophones in Canada live in New Brunswick.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"False. The majority of Francophones live in the province of Quebec; one million Francophones live in Ontario, New Brunswick and Manitoba.","diff":2},{"id":"who-030","chapter":2,"type":"tf","q":"According to the guide, gay and lesbian Canadians enjoy equal treatment under the law, including access to civil marriage.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"True. Canada's diversity includes gay and lesbian Canadians, who enjoy the full protection of and equal treatment under the law, including access to civil marriage.","diff":3},{"id":"mod-001","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"Who discovered insulin, a hormone to treat diabetes?","opts":["Wilder Penfield and John Hopps","Sir Frederick Banting and Charles Best","Alexander Graham Bell and Sandford Fleming","Matthew Evans and Henry Woodward"],"a":1,"expl":"Sir Frederick Banting of Toronto and Charles Best discovered insulin, which has saved 16 million lives worldwide.","diff":1},{"id":"mod-002","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"What was the name of Terry Fox's 1980 cross-country run to raise money for cancer research?","opts":["The Run for Canada","The Race of Courage","The Marathon of Hope","The Journey of Heroes"],"a":2,"expl":"In 1980, Terry Fox, a British Columbian who lost his right leg to cancer at age 18, began the \"Marathon of Hope\" to raise money for cancer research.","diff":1},{"id":"mod-003","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"Who invented basketball in 1891?","opts":["Canadian James Naismith","Wayne Gretzky","Donovan Bailey","Lord Grey"],"a":0,"expl":"Basketball was invented by Canadian James Naismith in 1891.","diff":1},{"id":"mod-004","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"The discovery of oil in 1947, which began Canada's modern energy industry, took place in which province?","opts":["Saskatchewan","Ontario","British Columbia","Alberta"],"a":3,"expl":"The discovery of oil in Alberta in 1947 began Canada's modern energy industry.","diff":1},{"id":"mod-005","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"The era of rapid change that Quebec experienced in the 1960s is known as the:","opts":["Quiet Revolution","Great Upheaval","October Crisis","Cultural Awakening"],"a":0,"expl":"Quebec experienced an era of rapid change in the 1960s known as the Quiet Revolution.","diff":1},{"id":"mod-006","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"What does the Official Languages Act of 1969 guarantee?","opts":["That every province must be officially bilingual","That all Canadians must learn both English and French","French and English services in the federal government across Canada","That Quebec may separate from Canada"],"a":2,"expl":"The Official Languages Act (1969) guarantees French and English services in the federal government across Canada. It followed the Royal Commission on Bilingualism and Biculturalism established in 1963.","diff":2},{"id":"mod-007","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"Canada joined the North American Aerospace Defence Command (NORAD) together with which country?","opts":["Great Britain","The United States","Australia","The Soviet Union"],"a":1,"expl":"Canada joined with the United States in the North American Aerospace Defence Command (NORAD).","diff":1},{"id":"mod-008","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"What is the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)?","opts":["A free trade agreement with the United States","An association of French-speaking countries","A United Nations peacekeeping mission","A military alliance of democratic countries of the West"],"a":3,"expl":"Canada joined with other democratic countries of the West to form the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), a military alliance, at the start of the Cold War.","diff":1},{"id":"mod-009","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"In which conflict did Canada participate in a UN operation defending South Korea, with 500 dead and 1,000 wounded?","opts":["The Korean War (1950-53)","The Vietnam War (1975)","The Cold War","The war in Afghanistan"],"a":0,"expl":"Canada participated in the UN operation defending South Korea in the Korean War (1950-53), with 500 dead and 1,000 wounded.","diff":2},{"id":"mod-010","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"When was unemployment insurance (now called \"employment insurance\") introduced by the federal government?","opts":["1927","1965","1940","1951"],"a":2,"expl":"Unemployment insurance was introduced by the federal government in 1940. Old Age Security was devised in 1927, and the Canada and Quebec Pension Plans in 1965.","diff":2},{"id":"mod-011","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"Old Age Security was devised as early as what year?","opts":["1940","1927","1965","1947"],"a":1,"expl":"Old Age Security was devised as early as 1927.","diff":2},{"id":"mod-012","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"In what year were the Canada and Quebec Pension Plans established?","opts":["1940","1927","1951","1965"],"a":3,"expl":"The Canada and Quebec Pension Plans were established in 1965.","diff":3},{"id":"mod-013","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"Who provides publicly funded education in Canada?","opts":["The provinces and territories","The federal government","Faith communities","Municipal governments"],"a":0,"expl":"Publicly funded education is provided by the provinces and territories.","diff":1},{"id":"mod-014","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"What happened to the Canadian Constitution in 1982?","opts":["It was replaced by the British North America Act","It was amended without the agreement of Quebec","It was rejected in a national referendum","It was suspended during the Cold War"],"a":1,"expl":"After much negotiation, in 1982 the Constitution was amended without the agreement of Quebec.","diff":2},{"id":"mod-015","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"In which years was Quebec sovereignty defeated in provincial referendums?","opts":["1963 and 1969","1970 and 1982","1980 and 1995","1948 and 1960"],"a":2,"expl":"The movement for Quebec sovereignty was defeated in a referendum in 1980, and sovereignty was again defeated in a second referendum in 1995.","diff":2},{"id":"mod-016","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"The Group of Seven, founded in 1920, developed a style of painting to capture what subject?","opts":["Portraits of historical figures","Modern abstract art","Scenes of city life","The rugged wilderness landscapes"],"a":3,"expl":"In the visual arts, Canada is historically perhaps best known for the Group of Seven, founded in 1920, who developed a style of painting to capture the rugged wilderness landscapes.","diff":1},{"id":"mod-017","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"What did Emily Carr paint?","opts":["The forests and Aboriginal artifacts of the West Coast","The Prairie wheat fields","Portraits of governors general","Arctic wildlife and Inuit communities"],"a":0,"expl":"Emily Carr painted the forests and Aboriginal artifacts of the West Coast.","diff":2},{"id":"mod-018","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"In 1956, about 37,000 refugees who escaped Soviet tyranny were welcomed to Canada from which country?","opts":["Vietnam","Hungary","Poland","Ukraine"],"a":1,"expl":"Canada welcomed thousands of refugees from Communist oppression, including about 37,000 who escaped Soviet tyranny in Hungary in 1956. Later, over 50,000 Vietnamese sought refuge in Canada after 1975.","diff":2},{"id":"mod-019","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"Which Canadian invention is Alexander Graham Bell associated with?","opts":["The snowmobile","The cardiac pacemaker","The telephone","The BlackBerry"],"a":2,"expl":"Alexander Graham Bell hit on the idea of the telephone at his summer house in Canada.","diff":2},{"id":"mod-020","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"What did Joseph-Armand Bombardier invent?","opts":["The telephone","Standard time zones","The electric light bulb","The snowmobile"],"a":3,"expl":"Joseph-Armand Bombardier invented the snowmobile, a light-weight winter vehicle.","diff":1},{"id":"mod-021","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"What did Sir Sandford Fleming invent?","opts":["The worldwide system of standard time zones","The first wireless voice message","The Canadarm","Insulin"],"a":0,"expl":"Sir Sandford Fleming invented the worldwide system of standard time zones.","diff":2},{"id":"mod-022","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"Reginald Fessenden contributed to the invention of radio by doing what?","opts":["Commercializing the light bulb","Sending the first wireless voice message in the world","Inventing the first cardiac pacemaker","Founding Research in Motion"],"a":1,"expl":"Reginald Fessenden contributed to the invention of radio, sending the first wireless voice message in the world.","diff":3},{"id":"mod-023","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"What did Dr. John A. Hopps invent?","opts":["Insulin","The snowmobile","The first cardiac pacemaker","The robotic arm"],"a":2,"expl":"Dr. John A. Hopps invented the first cardiac pacemaker, used today to save the lives of people with heart disorders.","diff":3},{"id":"mod-024","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"The Canadarm, a robotic arm used in outer space, was invented by:","opts":["Mike Lazaridis and Jim Balsillie","Matthew Evans and Henry Woodward","The Canadian Space Agency astronauts","SPAR Aerospace / National Research Council"],"a":3,"expl":"SPAR Aerospace / National Research Council invented the Canadarm, a robotic arm used in outer space.","diff":3},{"id":"mod-025","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"Mike Lazaridis and Jim Balsillie of Research in Motion (RIM) are known for which famous invention?","opts":["The BlackBerry","The Canadarm","The telephone","The radio"],"a":0,"expl":"Mike Lazaridis and Jim Balsillie of Research in Motion (RIM), a wireless communications company, are known for its most famous invention: the BlackBerry.","diff":3},{"id":"mod-026","chapter":4,"type":"mc","q":"Who scored the winning goal for Canada in the 1972 Canada-Soviet Summit Series, often called \"the goal heard around the world\"?","opts":["Wayne Gretzky","Paul Henderson","Donovan Bailey","Mark Tewksbury"],"a":1,"expl":"In 1972, Paul Henderson scored the winning goal for Canada in the Canada-Soviet Summit Series.","diff":3},{"id":"mod-027","chapter":4,"type":"tf","q":"Wayne Gretzky, one of the greatest hockey players of all time, played for the Edmonton Oilers from 1979 to 1988.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"True. One of the greatest hockey players of all time, Wayne Gretzky, played for the Edmonton Oilers from 1979 to 1988.","diff":1},{"id":"mod-028","chapter":4,"type":"tf","q":"In 1985, Rick Hansen circled the globe in a wheelchair to raise funds for cancer research.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"False. Rick Hansen circled the globe in a wheelchair to raise funds for spinal cord research. It was Terry Fox who ran to raise money for cancer research.","diff":2},{"id":"mod-029","chapter":4,"type":"tf","q":"Canada's high standard of living is maintained by the hard work of Canadians and by trade with other nations, in particular the United States.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"True. Canadians enjoy one of the world's highest standards of living, maintained by hard work and by trade with other nations, in particular the United States.","diff":1},{"id":"mod-030","chapter":4,"type":"tf","q":"Aboriginal people were granted the right to vote in federal elections in 1948.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"False. Aboriginal people were granted the vote in 1960. It was Japanese-Canadians who gained the right to vote in 1948.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-001","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"The remains of a Viking settlement in Canada, now a World Heritage site, are located at which place?","opts":["Port-Royal","L'Anse aux Meadows","Fort Garry","Fort Langley"],"a":1,"expl":"The Vikings from Iceland who colonized Greenland 1,000 years ago also reached Labrador and the island of Newfoundland. The remains of their settlement, l'Anse aux Meadows, are a World Heritage site.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-002","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Who, in 1497, was the first to draw a map of Canada's East Coast?","opts":["Jacques Cartier","Samuel de Champlain","John Cabot","Pierre de Monts"],"a":2,"expl":"European exploration began in earnest in 1497 with the expedition of John Cabot, who was the first to draw a map of Canada's East Coast.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-003","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Between 1534 and 1542, Jacques Cartier made three voyages across the Atlantic, claiming the land for whom?","opts":["King Francis I of France","King Charles II of England","King George V","Queen Victoria"],"a":0,"expl":"Jacques Cartier made three voyages between 1534 and 1542, claiming the land for King Francis I of France.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-004","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"The name 'Canada' comes from the Iroquoian word 'kanata.' What does it mean?","opts":["Great river","Meeting place","Land of the north","Village"],"a":3,"expl":"Cartier heard two captured guides speak the Iroquoian word kanata, meaning 'village.' By the 1550s, the name of Canada began appearing on maps.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-005","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Why did the first European explorers call the native peoples of Canada 'Indians'?","opts":["The first explorers thought they had reached the East Indies","They spoke languages related to those of India","Early maps labelled North America as India","The word means 'first peoples' in French"],"a":0,"expl":"Europeans called the native peoples 'Indians' because the first explorers thought they had reached the East Indies.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-006","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Which Aboriginal group was nomadic, following the bison (buffalo) herd?","opts":["The Huron-Wendat","The Cree","The Sioux","The Inuit"],"a":2,"expl":"The Sioux were nomadic, following the bison (buffalo) herd. The Huron-Wendat were farmers and hunters, the Cree and Dene were hunter-gatherers, and the Inuit lived off Arctic wildlife.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-007","chapter":3,"type":"tf","q":"Before European contact, West Coast natives preserved fish by drying and smoking.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"True. The guide states that West Coast natives preserved fish by drying and smoking.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-008","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"In 1604, the first European settlement north of Florida was established by which French explorers?","opts":["Jacques Cartier and Count Frontenac","Pierre de Monts and Samuel de Champlain","Jean Talon and Bishop Laval","James Wolfe and the Marquis de Montcalm"],"a":1,"expl":"In 1604, the first European settlement north of Florida was established by French explorers Pierre de Monts and Samuel de Champlain, first on St. Croix Island, then at Port-Royal, in Acadia.","diff":3},{"id":"hist-009","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"In 1608, Samuel de Champlain built a fortress at what is now which city?","opts":["Montreal","Port-Royal","Québec City","Halifax"],"a":2,"expl":"In 1608 Champlain built a fortress at what is now Québec City.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-010","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"The vast fur-trade economy of New France was driven by European demand for what?","opts":["Timber","Cod and other fish","Gold","Beaver pelts"],"a":3,"expl":"The French and Aboriginal people collaborated in the vast fur-trade economy, driven by the demand for beaver pelts in Europe.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-011","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"In 1670, King Charles II of England granted exclusive trading rights over the watershed draining into Hudson Bay to which company?","opts":["The North West Company","The Canadian Pacific Railway","The Montreal Stock Exchange","The Hudson's Bay Company"],"a":3,"expl":"In 1670, King Charles II of England granted the Hudson's Bay Company exclusive trading rights over the watershed draining into Hudson Bay.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-012","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"What did the British victory at the Battle of the Plains of Abraham in 1759 mark?","opts":["The start of the American Revolution","The end of France's empire in America","The beginning of the War of 1812","The union of Upper and Lower Canada"],"a":1,"expl":"In 1759, the British defeated the French in the Battle of the Plains of Abraham at Québec City, marking the end of France's empire in America.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-013","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Which two commanders were both killed leading their troops at the Battle of the Plains of Abraham?","opts":["Brigadier James Wolfe and the Marquis de Montcalm","Sir Isaac Brock and Chief Tecumseh","Count Frontenac and Pierre de Monts","Sir Guy Carleton and Charles de Salaberry"],"a":0,"expl":"The commanders of both armies, Brigadier James Wolfe and the Marquis de Montcalm, were killed leading their troops in battle in 1759.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-014","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"What did the Quebec Act of 1774 do for the French Roman Catholic majority?","opts":["It abolished slavery throughout the British Empire","It divided Quebec into Upper and Lower Canada","It united Upper and Lower Canada as the Province of Canada","It allowed religious freedom for Catholics and permitted them to hold public office"],"a":3,"expl":"The Quebec Act of 1774 allowed religious freedom for Catholics and permitted them to hold public office, a practice not then allowed in Britain.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-015","chapter":3,"type":"tf","q":"The Quebec Act of 1774 abolished French civil law in the Province of Quebec.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"False. The Quebec Act restored French civil law while maintaining British criminal law.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-016","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Who were the United Empire Loyalists?","opts":["People loyal to the Crown who fled the American Revolution","French colonists deported from Acadia","Fur traders working for the Hudson's Bay Company","Settlers who supported joining the United States"],"a":0,"expl":"More than 40,000 people loyal to the Crown, called 'Loyalists,' fled the oppression of the American Revolution to settle in Nova Scotia and Quebec.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-018","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Where was the first representative assembly in what is now Canada elected, in 1758?","opts":["Québec City","York (now Toronto)","Charlottetown","Halifax, Nova Scotia"],"a":3,"expl":"The first representative assembly was elected in Halifax, Nova Scotia, in 1758. Prince Edward Island followed in 1773 and New Brunswick in 1785.","diff":3},{"id":"hist-019","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"The Constitutional Act of 1791 divided the Province of Quebec into which two parts?","opts":["Canada East and Canada West","Upper Canada and Lower Canada","Ontario and Quebec","The Province of Canada and Rupert's Land"],"a":1,"expl":"The Constitutional Act of 1791 divided the Province of Quebec into Upper Canada (later Ontario), mainly Loyalist, Protestant and English-speaking, and Lower Canada (later Quebec), heavily Catholic and French-speaking.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-020","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Major-General Sir Isaac Brock captured Detroit in 1812 but was killed while defending against an American attack at which place?","opts":["Queenston Heights","Châteauguay","Beaver Dams","Fort Henry, Kingston"],"a":0,"expl":"In July 1812 Brock captured Detroit but was killed while defending against an American attack at Queenston Heights, near Niagara Falls, a battle the Americans lost.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-021","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"In 1813, Laura Secord made a dangerous 19-mile (30-km) journey on foot in order to do what?","opts":["Carry ammunition to Fort Garry","Deliver dispatches to the Duke of Wellington","Warn Lieutenant James FitzGibbon of a planned American attack","Guide Loyalist refugees to Nova Scotia"],"a":2,"expl":"In 1813, Laura Secord made a dangerous 19-mile (30-km) journey on foot to warn Lieutenant James FitzGibbon of a planned American attack. Her bravery contributed to victory at the Battle of Beaver Dams.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-022","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"In 1813, who led 460 soldiers, mostly French Canadiens, to turn back 4,000 American invaders at Châteauguay?","opts":["Major-General Robert Ross","Lieutenant-Colonel Charles de Salaberry","Major-General Sir Isaac Brock","Sir Guy Carleton"],"a":1,"expl":"In 1813, Lieutenant-Colonel Charles de Salaberry and 460 soldiers, mostly French Canadiens, turned back 4,000 American invaders at Châteauguay, south of Montreal.","diff":3},{"id":"hist-023","chapter":3,"type":"tf","q":"The War of 1812 helped ensure that Canada would remain independent of the United States.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"True. The present-day Canada-U.S.A. border is partly an outcome of the War of 1812, which ensured that Canada would remain independent of the United States.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-024","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"In what year did the British Parliament abolish slavery throughout the Empire?","opts":["1793","1807","1833","1867"],"a":2,"expl":"In 1807 the British Parliament prohibited the buying and selling of slaves, and in 1833 it abolished slavery throughout the Empire.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-025","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"What was the Underground Railroad?","opts":["A Christian anti-slavery network that helped slaves escape to Canada","The first railway line between Montreal and Toronto","A secret supply route used during the War of 1812","A trading route of the Hudson's Bay Company"],"a":0,"expl":"Thousands of slaves escaped from the United States, followed 'the North Star' and settled in Canada via the Underground Railroad, a Christian anti-slavery network.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-026","chapter":3,"type":"tf","q":"The armed rebellions of 1837-38 had broad public support and succeeded in overthrowing British rule.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"False. The rebels did not have enough public support to succeed and were defeated by British troops and Canadian volunteers; a number of rebels were hanged or exiled.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-027","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"After the rebellions of 1837-38, what did Lord Durham recommend?","opts":["That Canada join the United States","That the Hudson's Bay Company govern the West","That Quebec become an independent country","That Upper and Lower Canada be merged and given responsible government"],"a":3,"expl":"Lord Durham, an English reformer sent to report on the rebellions, recommended that Upper and Lower Canada be merged and given responsible government.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-028","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Under responsible government, what must happen if the government loses a confidence vote in the assembly?","opts":["The Governor appoints new ministers from London","It must resign","A new constitution must be written","The assembly is permanently dissolved"],"a":1,"expl":"Responsible government means the ministers of the Crown must have the support of a majority of the elected representatives; if the government loses a confidence vote in the assembly it must resign. This is the system we have today.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-029","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Which was the first British North American colony to attain full responsible government, in 1847-48?","opts":["Nova Scotia","United Canada","New Brunswick","Prince Edward Island"],"a":0,"expl":"The first British North American colony to attain full responsible government was Nova Scotia in 1847-48. In 1848-49 Lord Elgin introduced responsible government in United Canada.","diff":3},{"id":"hist-030","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Who were the Fathers of Confederation?","opts":["The first officers of the North West Mounted Police","The British governors of the Atlantic colonies","Representatives of Nova Scotia, New Brunswick and the Province of Canada","The first judges appointed in the Dominion of Canada"],"a":2,"expl":"From 1864 to 1867, representatives of Nova Scotia, New Brunswick and the Province of Canada, with British support, worked together to establish a new country. These men are known as the Fathers of Confederation.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-031","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"On what date was the Dominion of Canada officially born?","opts":["June 6, 1944","July 1, 1867","November 11, 1918","January 11, 1815"],"a":1,"expl":"The British Parliament passed the British North America Act in 1867, and the Dominion of Canada was officially born on July 1, 1867.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-032","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Which four provinces first formed the Dominion of Canada in 1867?","opts":["Ontario, Quebec, Nova Scotia and New Brunswick","Ontario, Quebec, Manitoba and British Columbia","Nova Scotia, New Brunswick, Prince Edward Island and Newfoundland","Ontario, Manitoba, Saskatchewan and Alberta"],"a":0,"expl":"The old Province of Canada was split into Ontario and Quebec, which, together with New Brunswick and Nova Scotia, formed the new country called the Dominion of Canada in 1867.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-033","chapter":3,"type":"tf","q":"Until 1982, July 1 was celebrated as 'Dominion Day.'","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"True. Until 1982, July 1 was celebrated as 'Dominion Day' to commemorate the day Canada became a self-governing Dominion. Today it is officially known as Canada Day.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-034","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Which Father of Confederation suggested the term 'Dominion of Canada' in 1864, inspired by Psalm 72 in the Bible?","opts":["Sir John A. Macdonald","Sir George-Étienne Cartier","Sir Étienne-Paschal Taché","Sir Leonard Tilley"],"a":3,"expl":"Sir Leonard Tilley, an elected official and Father of Confederation from New Brunswick, suggested the term Dominion of Canada in 1864, inspired by Psalm 72, which refers to 'dominion from sea to sea.'","diff":3},{"id":"hist-035","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Who became Canada's first Prime Minister in 1867?","opts":["Sir Wilfrid Laurier","Sir John Alexander Macdonald","Sir Louis-Hippolyte La Fontaine","Sir Robert Borden"],"a":1,"expl":"In 1867, Sir John Alexander Macdonald, a Father of Confederation, became Canada's first Prime Minister. Born in Scotland on January 11, 1815, his portrait is on the $10 bill.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-036","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Who was the key architect of Confederation from Quebec?","opts":["Sir Étienne-Paschal Taché","Sir Wilfrid Laurier","Sir George-Étienne Cartier","Louis Riel"],"a":2,"expl":"Sir George-Étienne Cartier was the key architect of Confederation from Quebec. He led Quebec into Confederation and helped negotiate the entry of the Northwest Territories, Manitoba and British Columbia into Canada.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-037","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Who led the armed uprising of the Métis at Red River and seized Fort Garry in 1869?","opts":["Louis Riel","Gabriel Dumont","Chief Tecumseh","Joseph Brant"],"a":0,"expl":"When Canada took over the northwest region in 1869, the 12,000 Métis of the Red River were not consulted. In response, Louis Riel led an armed uprising and seized Fort Garry, the territorial capital.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-038","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"What was the outcome for Louis Riel after the second Métis rebellion of 1885 in present-day Saskatchewan?","opts":["He became premier of Saskatchewan","He negotiated Manitoba's entry into Confederation","He was permanently exiled to the United States","He was tried and executed for high treason"],"a":3,"expl":"The second rebellion in 1885 led to Riel's trial and execution for high treason, a decision strongly opposed in Quebec. Riel is seen by many as a hero, a defender of Métis rights and the father of Manitoba.","diff":3},{"id":"hist-039","chapter":3,"type":"tf","q":"Louis Riel was elected to Parliament but never took his seat.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"True. After fleeing to the United States in 1870, Riel was elected to Parliament but never took his seat.","diff":3},{"id":"hist-040","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"British Columbia joined Canada in 1871 after Ottawa promised to do what?","opts":["Abolish the head tax","Establish a naval base at Victoria","Build a railway to the West Coast","Create the North West Mounted Police"],"a":2,"expl":"British Columbia joined Canada in 1871 after Ottawa promised to build a railway to the West Coast.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-041","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Who drove the last spike of the Canadian Pacific Railway on November 7, 1885?","opts":["Sir John A. Macdonald","Donald Smith (Lord Strathcona)","Sir Sam Steele","Sir Wilfrid Laurier"],"a":1,"expl":"On November 7, 1885, Donald Smith (Lord Strathcona), the Scottish-born director of the Canadian Pacific Railway, drove the last spike, completing a powerful symbol of unity.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-042","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"In what year did Alberta and Saskatchewan become provinces of Canada?","opts":["1867","1871","1898","1905"],"a":3,"expl":"Alberta and Saskatchewan joined Confederation in 1905. Manitoba and the Northwest Territories joined in 1870, British Columbia in 1871, and Yukon Territory in 1898.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-043","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Which province was the last to join Canada, in 1949?","opts":["Newfoundland and Labrador","Prince Edward Island","British Columbia","Manitoba"],"a":0,"expl":"Newfoundland and Labrador joined Canada in 1949. The territory of Nunavut was later established in 1999.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-044","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Who became the first French-Canadian prime minister since Confederation and encouraged immigration to the West?","opts":["Sir George-Étienne Cartier","Sir Wilfrid Laurier","Sir Louis-Hippolyte La Fontaine","Sir Robert Borden"],"a":1,"expl":"Sir Wilfrid Laurier became the first French-Canadian prime minister since Confederation and encouraged immigration to the West. His portrait is on the $5 bill.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-045","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"About how many Canadians served in the First World War, out of a total population of eight million?","opts":["About 60,000","About 260,000","More than 600,000","More than seven million"],"a":2,"expl":"More than 600,000 Canadians served in the First World War, most of them volunteers, out of a total population of eight million. In total, 60,000 Canadians were killed and 170,000 wounded.","diff":3},{"id":"hist-046","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"In April 1917, the Canadian Corps secured its reputation as the 'shock troops of the British Empire' by capturing what?","opts":["Vimy Ridge","Juno Beach","Dieppe","Hong Kong"],"a":0,"expl":"The Canadian Corps captured Vimy Ridge in April 1917, with 10,000 killed or wounded, securing the Canadians' reputation for valour as the 'shock troops of the British Empire.'","diff":1},{"id":"hist-047","chapter":3,"type":"tf","q":"Vimy Day is celebrated on November 11.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"False. April 9 is celebrated as Vimy Day, marking the capture of Vimy Ridge in 1917. November 11 is Remembrance Day.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-048","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Who commanded the Canadian Corps in 1918 and is described as Canada's greatest soldier?","opts":["Sir Isaac Brock","Sir Sam Steele","Major-General Robert Ross","General Sir Arthur Currie"],"a":3,"expl":"In 1918, under the command of General Sir Arthur Currie, Canada's greatest soldier, the Canadian Corps advanced alongside the French and British Empire troops in the last hundred days of the war.","diff":3},{"id":"hist-049","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"The First World War ended with the Armistice on what date?","opts":["April 9, 1917","November 11, 1918","May 8, 1945","August 8, 1918"],"a":1,"expl":"With Germany and Austria's surrender, the war ended in the Armistice on November 11, 1918. Canadians now observe Remembrance Day each year on November 11.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-050","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Who composed the poem 'In Flanders Fields' in 1915?","opts":["Stephen Leacock","Sir Arthur Currie","Lieutenant-Colonel John McCrae","Émile Nelligan"],"a":2,"expl":"Canadian medical officer Lieutenant-Colonel John McCrae composed the poem 'In Flanders Fields' in 1915; it is often recited on Remembrance Day.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-051","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Who founded the women's suffrage movement in Canada and was the first Canadian woman to practise medicine in Canada?","opts":["Dr. Emily Stowe","Agnes Macphail","Thérèse Casgrain","Laura Secord"],"a":0,"expl":"The founder of the women's suffrage movement in Canada was Dr. Emily Stowe, the first Canadian woman to practise medicine in Canada.","diff":3},{"id":"hist-052","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"In 1916, which province became the first to grant voting rights to women?","opts":["Ontario","Quebec","Nova Scotia","Manitoba"],"a":3,"expl":"In 1916, Manitoba became the first province to grant voting rights to women. In 1918, most Canadian female citizens aged 21 and over were granted the right to vote in federal elections; Quebec granted women the vote in 1940.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-053","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Who became the first woman Member of Parliament in 1921?","opts":["Dr. Emily Stowe","Agnes Macphail","Mary Ann Shadd Cary","Thérèse Casgrain"],"a":1,"expl":"In 1921 Agnes Macphail, a farmer and teacher, became the first woman MP.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-054","chapter":3,"type":"tf","q":"Agnes Macphail was the first Canadian woman to practise medicine in Canada.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"False. Agnes Macphail was the first woman MP (1921). Dr. Emily Stowe was the first Canadian woman to practise medicine in Canada and founded the suffrage movement.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-055","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"What did the stock market crash of 1929 lead to?","opts":["The Roaring Twenties","The First World War","The Great Depression","Confederation"],"a":2,"expl":"The stock market crash of 1929 led to the Great Depression or the 'Dirty Thirties.' Unemployment reached 27% in 1933 and many businesses were wiped out.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-056","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"Why was the Bank of Canada created in 1934?","opts":["To manage the money supply and bring stability to the financial system","To finance the building of the Canadian Pacific Railway","To replace the Montreal Stock Exchange","To pay unemployment insurance during the Depression"],"a":0,"expl":"The Bank of Canada, a central bank to manage the money supply and bring stability to the financial system, was created in 1934.","diff":3},{"id":"hist-057","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"How did the Second World War begin in 1939?","opts":["Japan attacked Hong Kong","Germany attacked Belgium and France and Britain declared war","The stock market crashed","Adolf Hitler, the Nazi dictator of Germany, invaded Poland"],"a":3,"expl":"The Second World War began in 1939 when Adolf Hitler, the National Socialist (Nazi) dictator of Germany, invaded Poland and conquered much of Europe.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-058","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"On D-Day, June 6, 1944, 15,000 Canadian troops stormed and captured which beach from the German Army?","opts":["Omaha Beach","Dieppe","Juno Beach","Vimy Ridge"],"a":2,"expl":"In the invasion of Normandy on June 6, 1944, known as D-Day, 15,000 Canadian troops stormed and captured Juno Beach from the German Army, a great national achievement.","diff":1},{"id":"hist-059","chapter":3,"type":"tf","q":"Approximately one in ten Allied soldiers on D-Day was Canadian.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"True. Approximately one in ten Allied soldiers on D-Day was Canadian. The Canadian Army went on to liberate the Netherlands in 1944-45.","diff":2},{"id":"hist-060","chapter":3,"type":"mc","q":"In what year were Aboriginal people granted the right to vote?","opts":["1867","1918","1948","1960"],"a":3,"expl":"Aboriginal people were granted the vote in 1960. In 1948 the Japanese-Canadians, the last Canadians of Asian descent denied the franchise, gained the right to vote.","diff":2},{"id":"gov-001","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"What are the three key facts about Canada's system of government?","opts":["A republic, a direct democracy and a federation","A constitutional republic, a monarchy and a confederation","A federal state, a parliamentary democracy and a constitutional monarchy","A unitary state, a presidential democracy and a constitutional monarchy"],"a":2,"expl":"There are three key facts about Canada's system of government: our country is a federal state, a parliamentary democracy and a constitutional monarchy.","diff":1},{"id":"gov-002","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"In which document were the responsibilities of the federal and provincial governments defined in 1867?","opts":["The British North America Act, now known as the Constitution Act, 1867","The Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms","The Statute of Westminster","The Quebec Act"],"a":0,"expl":"The responsibilities of the federal and provincial governments were defined in 1867 in the British North America Act, now known as the Constitution Act, 1867.","diff":2},{"id":"gov-003","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"Which of the following is a responsibility of the federal government?","opts":["Education","National defence","Highways","Natural resources"],"a":1,"expl":"The federal government takes responsibility for matters of national and international concern, including defence, foreign policy, interprovincial trade and communications, currency, navigation, criminal law and citizenship.","diff":1},{"id":"gov-004","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"Which of the following is a responsibility of the provinces?","opts":["Currency","Foreign policy","National defence","Education"],"a":3,"expl":"The provinces are responsible for municipal government, education, health, natural resources, property and civil rights, and highways.","diff":1},{"id":"gov-005","chapter":5,"type":"tf","q":"The federal government and the provinces share jurisdiction over agriculture and immigration.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"The guide states that the federal government and the provinces share jurisdiction over agriculture and immigration.","diff":2},{"id":"gov-006","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"What are the three parts of Parliament?","opts":["The Prime Minister, the Cabinet and the House of Commons","The Sovereign (Queen or King), the Senate and the House of Commons","The Governor General, the Supreme Court and the Senate","The House of Commons, the Senate and the provincial legislatures"],"a":1,"expl":"Parliament has three parts: the Sovereign (Queen or King), the Senate and the House of Commons.","diff":1},{"id":"gov-007","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"What do provincial legislatures comprise?","opts":["The Lieutenant Governor and the elected Assembly","The Premier and the Senate","The Commissioner and the elected Assembly","The Governor General and the Legislative Assembly"],"a":0,"expl":"Provincial legislatures comprise the Lieutenant Governor and the elected Assembly.","diff":3},{"id":"gov-008","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"In the federal government, who selects the Cabinet ministers and is responsible for the operations and policy of the government?","opts":["The Governor General","The Sovereign","The Prime Minister","The Speaker of the House of Commons"],"a":2,"expl":"In the federal government, the Prime Minister selects the Cabinet ministers and is responsible for the operations and policy of the government.","diff":1},{"id":"gov-009","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"How are members of the House of Commons chosen?","opts":["They are appointed by the Governor General","They are appointed by the Prime Minister","They are chosen by the provincial premiers","They are elected by the people, traditionally every four years"],"a":3,"expl":"The House of Commons is the representative chamber, made up of members of Parliament elected by the people, traditionally every four years.","diff":1},{"id":"gov-010","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"How are senators chosen?","opts":["Appointed by the Governor General on the Prime Minister's advice","Elected by the people every four years","Appointed by the Supreme Court","Elected by the provincial legislatures"],"a":0,"expl":"Senators are appointed by the Governor General on the advice of the Prime Minister and serve until age 75.","diff":2},{"id":"gov-011","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"Until what age do senators serve?","opts":["65","70","75","80"],"a":2,"expl":"Senators are appointed by the Governor General on the advice of the Prime Minister and serve until age 75.","diff":2},{"id":"gov-012","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"Who grants royal assent to bills on behalf of the Sovereign?","opts":["The Prime Minister","The Governor General","The Chief Justice of the Supreme Court","The Speaker of the Senate"],"a":1,"expl":"No bill can become law until it has been passed by both chambers and has received royal assent, granted by the Governor General on behalf of the Sovereign.","diff":2},{"id":"gov-013","chapter":5,"type":"tf","q":"A bill can become law in Canada after being passed by the House of Commons alone, without the Senate.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"No bill can become law in Canada until it has been passed by both chambers (the House of Commons and the Senate) and has received royal assent.","diff":2},{"id":"gov-014","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"What happens at the First Reading stage of the legislative process?","opts":["The bill is considered read for the first time and is printed","Members debate the bill's principle","The bill receives royal assent","Committee members study the bill clause by clause"],"a":0,"expl":"Step 1, First Reading: the bill is considered read for the first time and is printed.","diff":2},{"id":"gov-015","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"At which stage of the legislative process do committee members study a bill clause by clause?","opts":["First Reading","Report Stage","Third Reading","Committee Stage"],"a":3,"expl":"Step 3, Committee Stage: committee members study the bill clause by clause.","diff":3},{"id":"gov-016","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"What is the final step before a bill becomes law?","opts":["Third Reading","Report Stage","Royal Assent","Second Reading in the Senate"],"a":2,"expl":"Step 7, Royal Assent: the bill receives royal assent after being passed by both Houses.","diff":2},{"id":"gov-017","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"Who is Canada's head of state?","opts":["A hereditary Sovereign (Queen or King)","The Prime Minister","The Governor General","The Chief Justice of Canada"],"a":0,"expl":"As a constitutional monarchy, Canada's head of state is a hereditary Sovereign (Queen or King), who reigns in accordance with the Constitution: the rule of law.","diff":1},{"id":"gov-018","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"Who is the head of government in Canada, the person who actually directs the governing of the country?","opts":["The Sovereign","The Prime Minister","The Governor General","The Speaker of the House of Commons"],"a":1,"expl":"There is a clear distinction between the head of state—the Sovereign—and the head of government—the Prime Minister, who actually directs the governing of the country.","diff":1},{"id":"gov-019","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"As Head of the Commonwealth, the Sovereign links Canada to how many other nations?","opts":["27","13","45","53"],"a":3,"expl":"As Head of the Commonwealth, the Sovereign links Canada to 53 other nations that cooperate to advance social, economic and cultural progress.","diff":3},{"id":"gov-020","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"How is the Governor General chosen?","opts":["Elected by the people every five years","Appointed by the Senate","Appointed by the Sovereign on the advice of the Prime Minister","Chosen by a vote of the House of Commons"],"a":2,"expl":"The Sovereign is represented in Canada by the Governor General, who is appointed by the Sovereign on the advice of the Prime Minister, usually for five years.","diff":2},{"id":"gov-021","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"Who represents the Sovereign in each of the ten provinces?","opts":["The Premier","The Lieutenant Governor","The Commissioner","The Speaker of the Legislative Assembly"],"a":1,"expl":"In each of the ten provinces, the Sovereign is represented by the Lieutenant Governor, who is appointed by the Governor General on the advice of the Prime Minister, normally for five years.","diff":2},{"id":"gov-022","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"What are the three branches of government in Canada?","opts":["Executive, Legislative and Judicial","Federal, Provincial and Municipal","The Sovereign, the Senate and the House of Commons","Parliament, the Cabinet and the Crown"],"a":0,"expl":"The interplay between the three branches of government—the Executive, Legislative and Judicial—helps to secure the rights and freedoms of Canadians.","diff":1},{"id":"gov-023","chapter":5,"type":"tf","q":"Cabinet ministers must retain the \"confidence of the House\" and have to resign if they are defeated in a non-confidence vote.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"Cabinet ministers are responsible to the elected representatives, which means they must retain the confidence of the House and have to resign if they are defeated in a non-confidence vote.","diff":2},{"id":"gov-024","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"In each province, who has a role similar to that of the Prime Minister in the federal government?","opts":["The Lieutenant Governor","The Commissioner","The Mayor","The Premier"],"a":3,"expl":"In each province, the Premier has a role similar to that of the Prime Minister in the federal government, just as the Lieutenant Governor has a role similar to that of the Governor General.","diff":1},{"id":"gov-025","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"In the three territories, what is the role of the Commissioner?","opts":["To pass territorial laws","To represent the federal government and play a ceremonial role","To lead the territorial government as head of government","To represent the Sovereign as head of state"],"a":1,"expl":"In the three territories, the Commissioner represents the federal government and plays a ceremonial role.","diff":2},{"id":"gov-026","chapter":5,"type":"tf","q":"The three northern territories do not have the status of provinces, but their governments and assemblies carry out many of the same functions.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"The three northern territories, which have small populations, do not have the status of provinces, but their governments and assemblies carry out many of the same functions.","diff":2},{"id":"gov-027","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"Depending on the province or territory, members of the legislature may be called all of the following EXCEPT:","opts":["Members of the Legislative Assembly (MLAs)","Members of the National Assembly (MNAs)","Members of the Provincial Parliament (MPPs)","Senators"],"a":3,"expl":"Members of provincial and territorial legislatures are called MLAs, MNAs, MPPs or MHAs (members of the House of Assembly), depending on the province or territory. Senators sit in the federal Senate.","diff":3},{"id":"gov-028","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"How many judges sit on the Supreme Court of Canada, and who appoints them?","opts":["Nine judges appointed by the Governor General","Seven judges appointed by the Prime Minister","Nine judges elected by the provinces","Twelve judges appointed by the Senate"],"a":0,"expl":"The Supreme Court of Canada has nine judges appointed by the Governor General.","diff":3},{"id":"gov-029","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"What are the laws passed by municipal governments called?","opts":["Statutes","Ordinances","By-laws","Regulations"],"a":2,"expl":"Municipal governments usually have a council that passes laws called by-laws that affect only the local community.","diff":1},{"id":"gov-030","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"Who usually makes up a municipal council?","opts":["A premier and MLAs","A mayor (or a reeve) and councillors or aldermen","A commissioner and band councillors","A lieutenant governor and aldermen"],"a":1,"expl":"The municipal council usually includes a mayor (or a reeve) and councillors or aldermen.","diff":2},{"id":"gov-031","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"Which level of government is normally responsible for garbage removal, snow removal and firefighting?","opts":["Federal","Provincial","Territorial","Municipal (local)"],"a":3,"expl":"Municipalities are normally responsible for urban or regional planning, streets and roads, sanitation such as garbage removal, snow removal, firefighting, emergency services, recreation facilities and public transit.","diff":1},{"id":"gov-032","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"Who has major responsibilities on First Nations reserves, including housing, schools and other services?","opts":["Band chiefs and councillors","Lieutenant governors","Municipal mayors","Territorial commissioners"],"a":0,"expl":"The First Nations have band chiefs and councillors who have major responsibilities on First Nations reserves, including housing, schools and other services.","diff":3},{"id":"gov-033","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"In Canada's constitutional monarchy, how does the Sovereign reign?","opts":["By directing the day-to-day governing of the country","By commanding the House of Commons","In accordance with the Constitution: the rule of law","By appointing all members of Parliament"],"a":2,"expl":"Canada's head of state is a hereditary Sovereign (Queen or King), who reigns in accordance with the Constitution: the rule of law. The Sovereign plays an important, non-partisan role.","diff":2},{"id":"gov-034","chapter":5,"type":"mc","q":"Which of the following countries is NOT listed in the guide as a constitutional monarchy?","opts":["Denmark and Norway","Japan","Sweden","The United States"],"a":3,"expl":"Other constitutional monarchies include Denmark, Norway, Sweden, Australia, New Zealand, The Netherlands, Spain, Thailand, Japan, Jordan and Morocco. The United States is not a monarchy.","diff":3},{"id":"gov-035","chapter":5,"type":"tf","q":"The Prime Minister is Canada's head of state.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"The head of state is the Sovereign; the Prime Minister is the head of government, who actually directs the governing of the country.","diff":1},{"id":"elec-001","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"Which of the following are the requirements to vote in a federal election?","opts":["Be a Canadian citizen, at least 16 years old, and own property","Be a Canadian citizen, at least 18 years old on voting day, and on the voters' list","Be a permanent resident, at least 18 years old, and employed","Be a Canadian citizen, at least 21 years old, and registered with a political party"],"a":1,"expl":"You are eligible to vote in a federal election if you are a Canadian citizen, at least 18 years old on voting day, and on the voters' list.","diff":1},{"id":"elec-002","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"From what database are the voters' lists used during federal elections produced?","opts":["The Canadian Citizenship Registry","The federal census","Provincial driver's licence records","The National Register of Electors"],"a":3,"expl":"The voters' lists are produced from the National Register of Electors by Elections Canada, a permanent database of Canadian citizens 18 years of age or older who are qualified to vote.","diff":3},{"id":"elec-003","chapter":6,"type":"tf","q":"Elections Canada is a neutral agency of Parliament.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"The voters' lists are produced from the National Register of Electors by a neutral agency of Parliament called Elections Canada.","diff":2},{"id":"elec-004","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"What information is on the voter information card mailed to electors once an election has been called?","opts":["When and where you vote, and a number to call for special services","The names of all candidates in your riding","Your assigned ballot number","Instructions on which party to vote for"],"a":0,"expl":"Elections Canada mails a voter information card to each elector in the National Register of Electors. The card lists when and where you vote and the number to call if you require an interpreter or other special services.","diff":1},{"id":"elec-005","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"What should you do if you do not receive a voter information card?","opts":["Wait until the next election to vote","Ask your employer to register you","Call your local elections office or Elections Canada","Visit the Prime Minister's office"],"a":2,"expl":"If you do not receive a voter information card, call your local elections office to ensure you are on the voters' list. If you do not have the number, call Elections Canada in Ottawa.","diff":2},{"id":"elec-006","chapter":6,"type":"tf","q":"If you are not on the voters' list, you cannot be added on election day.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"Even if you choose not to be listed in the National Register of Electors or do not receive a voter information card, you can still be added to the voters' list at any time, including on election day.","diff":2},{"id":"elec-007","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"What does the right to a secret ballot mean?","opts":["You must keep your vote secret and may never discuss it","No one can watch you vote and no one should look at how you voted","Only election officers may know how you voted","Your vote is recorded under a secret code linked to your name"],"a":1,"expl":"Canadian law secures the right to a secret ballot: no one can watch you vote and no one should look at how you voted. You may choose to discuss your vote, but no one has the right to insist you tell them.","diff":1},{"id":"elec-008","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"By law, when must federal elections be held?","opts":["On the first Tuesday of November every four years","On the third Monday of June every five years","Whenever the Senate decides","On the third Monday in October every four years"],"a":3,"expl":"Under legislation passed by Parliament, federal elections must be held on the third Monday in October every four years following the most recent general election.","diff":1},{"id":"elec-009","chapter":6,"type":"tf","q":"The Prime Minister may ask the Governor General to call an election earlier than the fixed date.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"The guide states that the Prime Minister may ask the Governor General to call an earlier election.","diff":2},{"id":"elec-010","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"According to the guide, into how many electoral districts is Canada divided?","opts":["208","105","308","338"],"a":2,"expl":"The guide states that Canada is divided into 308 electoral districts, also known as ridings or constituencies.","diff":3},{"id":"elec-011","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"What are electoral districts also known as?","opts":["Ridings or constituencies","Wards or boroughs","Counties or townships","Precincts or divisions"],"a":0,"expl":"Canada is divided into electoral districts, also known as ridings or constituencies. An electoral district is a geographical area represented by a member of Parliament.","diff":1},{"id":"elec-012","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"How many members of Parliament do the citizens in each electoral district elect?","opts":["Two","One","One per political party","It depends on the population of the district"],"a":1,"expl":"The citizens in each electoral district elect one MP who sits in the House of Commons to represent them, as well as all Canadians.","diff":1},{"id":"elec-013","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"Who may run as a candidate in a federal election?","opts":["Any resident of Canada over 21","Only members of a registered political party","Canadian citizens who are 18 years old or older","Only citizens born in Canada"],"a":2,"expl":"Canadian citizens who are 18 years old or older may run in a federal election. The people who run for office are called candidates.","diff":2},{"id":"elec-014","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"Who becomes the MP for an electoral district after an election?","opts":["The candidate chosen by the Governor General","The candidate appointed by the party with the most seats","The candidate with the most years of experience","The candidate who receives the most votes"],"a":3,"expl":"The people in each electoral district vote for the candidate and political party of their choice. The candidate who receives the most votes becomes the MP for that electoral district.","diff":1},{"id":"elec-015","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"Ordinarily, after an election, who is invited by the Governor General to form the government?","opts":["The leader of the political party with the most seats in the House of Commons","The leader of the party with the most votes nationwide","The longest-serving member of Parliament","The Speaker of the House of Commons"],"a":0,"expl":"Ordinarily, after an election, the leader of the political party with the most seats in the House of Commons is invited by the Governor General to form the government, and becomes the Prime Minister.","diff":1},{"id":"elec-016","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"What is a majority government?","opts":["When the party in power holds every seat in the Senate","When the party in power wins the most votes nationally","When the party in power holds at least half of the seats in the House of Commons","When two parties agree to govern together"],"a":2,"expl":"If the party in power holds at least half of the seats in the House of Commons, this is called a majority government.","diff":1},{"id":"elec-017","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"What is a minority government?","opts":["When the party in power has fewer senators than the opposition","When the party in power holds less than half of the seats in the House of Commons","When the smallest party in Parliament forms the government","When the Governor General governs directly"],"a":1,"expl":"If the party in power holds less than half of the seats in the House of Commons, this is called a minority government.","diff":1},{"id":"elec-018","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"How long do the Prime Minister and the party in power run the government?","opts":["As long as they have the support or confidence of the majority of the MPs","For a fixed term of exactly four years, no matter what","Until the Sovereign chooses a new Prime Minister","Until the Senate votes to replace them"],"a":0,"expl":"The Prime Minister and the party in power run the government as long as they have the support or confidence of the majority of the MPs.","diff":2},{"id":"elec-019","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"When the House of Commons votes on a major issue such as the budget, what is this considered?","opts":["A free vote","A procedural vote","A referendum","A matter of confidence"],"a":3,"expl":"When the House of Commons votes on a major issue such as the budget, this is considered a matter of confidence. If the government is defeated, the Prime Minister usually asks for an election to be called.","diff":3},{"id":"elec-020","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"What usually happens if a majority of the members of the House of Commons vote against a major government decision?","opts":["The Senate takes over the government","The Prime Minister asks the Governor General to call an election","The Supreme Court appoints a new Prime Minister","The vote is simply repeated until it passes"],"a":1,"expl":"If a majority of MPs vote against a major government decision, the party in power is defeated, which usually results in the Prime Minister asking the Governor General, on behalf of the Sovereign, to call an election.","diff":2},{"id":"elec-021","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"What are Cabinet ministers responsible for?","opts":["Counting ballots after an election","Appointing senators","Running the federal government departments","Representing the Sovereign in the provinces"],"a":2,"expl":"Cabinet ministers are responsible for running the federal government departments. The Prime Minister and the Cabinet ministers are called the Cabinet; they prepare the budget and propose most new laws.","diff":2},{"id":"elec-022","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"From where does the Prime Minister choose most of the ministers of the Crown?","opts":["From among members of the House of Commons","From among senior public servants","From among the provincial premiers","From among judges of the federal courts"],"a":0,"expl":"The Prime Minister chooses the ministers of the Crown, most of them from among members of the House of Commons.","diff":3},{"id":"elec-023","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"Which party becomes the Official Opposition (Her Majesty's Loyal Opposition)?","opts":["The party that has been in Parliament the longest","The party chosen by the Governor General","The party with the most senators","The opposition party with the most members of the House of Commons"],"a":3,"expl":"The opposition party with the most members of the House of Commons is the Official Opposition or Her Majesty's Loyal Opposition.","diff":2},{"id":"elec-024","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"What is the role of the opposition parties?","opts":["To run the federal government departments","To appoint Cabinet ministers","To peacefully oppose or try to improve government proposals","To organize federal elections"],"a":2,"expl":"The role of opposition parties is to peacefully oppose or try to improve government proposals.","diff":1},{"id":"elec-025","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"According to the guide, which three major political parties are represented in the House of Commons?","opts":["The Conservative Party, the New Democratic Party and the Liberal Party","The Liberal Party, the Green Party and the Reform Party","The Conservative Party, the Bloc Québécois and the Green Party","The New Democratic Party, the Labour Party and the Liberal Party"],"a":0,"expl":"The guide states there are three major political parties currently represented in the House of Commons: the Conservative Party, the New Democratic Party, and the Liberal Party.","diff":3},{"id":"elec-026","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"What can you do if you cannot or do not wish to vote on election day?","opts":["Ask a family member to vote for you","Vote by telephone","Skip the election; there is no other option","Vote at the advance polls or by special ballot"],"a":3,"expl":"If you cannot or do not wish to vote on election day, you can vote at the advance polls or by special ballot. The dates and location are on your voter information card.","diff":1},{"id":"elec-027","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"How do you mark a federal election ballot?","opts":["Write the name of your chosen party at the bottom","Mark an \"X\" in the circle next to the name of the candidate of your choice","Number the candidates in order of preference","Check a box beside the party leader's name"],"a":1,"expl":"Mark an \"X\" in the circle next to the name of the candidate of your choice. Once marked, fold the ballot and present it to the poll officials.","diff":2},{"id":"elec-028","chapter":6,"type":"mc","q":"What happens immediately after the polling stations close?","opts":["Election officers count the ballots and the results are made public","The ballots are sealed for one week before counting","The Governor General counts the ballots","The results are kept secret until Parliament resumes"],"a":0,"expl":"Immediately after the polling stations close, election officers count the ballots and the results are announced on radio, television and in newspapers, and on the Elections Canada website.","diff":2},{"id":"elec-029","chapter":6,"type":"tf","q":"The rules for provincial, territorial and municipal elections are exactly the same as those for federal elections.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"Provincial, territorial and municipal elections are held by secret ballot, but the rules are not the same as those for federal elections. It is important to find out the rules so you can exercise your right to vote.","diff":2},{"id":"elec-030","chapter":6,"type":"tf","q":"Your employer or union representative has the right to insist that you tell them how you voted.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"No one, including family members, your employer or union representative, has the right to insist that you tell them how you voted.","diff":1},{"id":"just-001","chapter":7,"type":"mc","q":"What is the highest court in Canada?","opts":["The Federal Court of Canada","The Court of Queen's Bench","The Supreme Court of Canada","The Court of Appeal"],"a":2,"expl":"The Supreme Court of Canada is the country's highest court. The Federal Court deals with matters concerning the federal government.","diff":1},{"id":"just-002","chapter":7,"type":"mc","q":"What is the presumption of innocence?","opts":["Everyone is innocent until proven guilty","Everyone is guilty until proven innocent","Only citizens are presumed innocent","Judges decide innocence before a trial begins"],"a":0,"expl":"Canada's judicial system is founded on the presumption of innocence in criminal matters, meaning everyone is innocent until proven guilty.","diff":1},{"id":"just-003","chapter":7,"type":"mc","q":"Who makes the laws in Canada?","opts":["The police","Elected representatives","Judges","The Royal Canadian Mounted Police"],"a":1,"expl":"Laws are written rules made by elected representatives. The courts settle disputes and the police enforce the laws.","diff":1},{"id":"just-004","chapter":7,"type":"mc","q":"What does the Federal Court of Canada deal with?","opts":["Lesser offences and traffic violations","Civil cases involving small sums of money","Family disputes","Matters concerning the federal government"],"a":3,"expl":"The Federal Court of Canada deals with matters concerning the federal government.","diff":2},{"id":"just-005","chapter":7,"type":"mc","q":"Which two provinces have their own provincial police forces?","opts":["Ontario and Quebec","Alberta and Saskatchewan","British Columbia and Manitoba","Nova Scotia and New Brunswick"],"a":0,"expl":"There are provincial police forces in Ontario and Quebec. The RCMP serves as the provincial police everywhere else.","diff":2},{"id":"just-006","chapter":7,"type":"mc","q":"What is the role of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police (RCMP)?","opts":["To enforce municipal by-laws only","To serve only as Ontario's provincial police","To enforce federal laws throughout Canada","To settle disputes in court"],"a":2,"expl":"The RCMP enforces federal laws throughout Canada, and serves as the provincial police in all provinces and territories except Ontario and Quebec, as well as in some municipalities.","diff":2},{"id":"just-007","chapter":7,"type":"mc","q":"What is meant by 'due process'?","opts":["Courts must process cases within one year","The government must respect all the legal rights a person is entitled to under the law","The police must obtain permission before patrolling","Everyone must be tried by a jury"],"a":1,"expl":"Due process is the principle that the government must respect all the legal rights a person is entitled to under the law.","diff":2},{"id":"just-008","chapter":7,"type":"mc","q":"What can you do if you cannot afford to pay for a lawyer?","opts":["You must represent yourself in court","You must ask the police to act for you","Your case is automatically dismissed","You can use legal aid services, free of charge or at low cost"],"a":3,"expl":"If you cannot pay for a lawyer, in most communities there are legal aid services available free of charge or at a low cost.","diff":1},{"id":"just-009","chapter":7,"type":"tf","q":"In Canada, the law applies to everyone except judges, politicians and the police.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"False. The law in Canada applies to everyone, including judges, politicians and the police.","diff":1},{"id":"just-010","chapter":7,"type":"mc","q":"What is the role of the courts in Canada?","opts":["To make new laws","To enforce the laws","To settle disputes","To elect representatives"],"a":2,"expl":"The courts settle disputes; the police enforce the laws; laws are made by elected representatives.","diff":1},{"id":"just-011","chapter":7,"type":"mc","q":"In most provinces, what is the trial court sometimes called?","opts":["The Court of Queen's Bench or the Supreme Court","The Federal Court of Appeal","The Small Claims Court","The Traffic Court"],"a":0,"expl":"In most provinces there is an appeal court and a trial court, sometimes called the Court of Queen's Bench or the Supreme Court.","diff":3},{"id":"just-012","chapter":7,"type":"mc","q":"What kinds of cases do small claims courts deal with?","opts":["Federal government matters","Criminal cases involving violence","Appeals from provincial courts","Civil cases involving small sums of money"],"a":3,"expl":"There are small claims courts for civil cases involving small sums of money, as well as provincial courts for lesser offences, family courts and traffic courts.","diff":2},{"id":"just-013","chapter":7,"type":"mc","q":"What does the blindfolded Lady Justice symbolize?","opts":["The secrecy of court proceedings","The impartial administration of our laws, blind to all but the facts","The right to remain silent","The presumption of guilt in civil matters"],"a":1,"expl":"The blindfolded Lady Justice symbolizes the impartial manner in which our laws are administered: blind to all considerations but the facts.","diff":3},{"id":"just-014","chapter":7,"type":"tf","q":"In Canada, you are allowed to question the police about their service or conduct.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"True. Almost all police forces in Canada have a process by which you can bring your concerns to the police and seek action.","diff":1},{"id":"just-015","chapter":7,"type":"mc","q":"Canada's legal system is based on a heritage that includes which of the following?","opts":["The rule of law, freedom under the law, democratic principles and due process","Military tradition, royal decrees and colonial charters","Trial by combat and common consensus","Religious law and customary punishment"],"a":0,"expl":"Canada's legal system is based on a heritage that includes the rule of law, freedom under the law, democratic principles and due process.","diff":2},{"id":"just-016","chapter":7,"type":"mc","q":"Who enforces the laws in Canada?","opts":["Elected representatives","Lawyers","The police","The courts"],"a":2,"expl":"The police enforce the laws and are there to keep people safe. The courts settle disputes.","diff":1},{"id":"just-017","chapter":7,"type":"mc","q":"Which courts deal with lesser offences?","opts":["The Supreme Court of Canada","The Federal Court of Canada","The appeal courts","Provincial courts"],"a":3,"expl":"There are provincial courts for lesser offences, as well as family courts, traffic courts and small claims courts.","diff":2},{"id":"just-018","chapter":7,"type":"mc","q":"According to the guide, what are Canada's laws intended to do?","opts":["Increase government revenue and limit free speech","Provide order, settle disputes peacefully, and express Canadians' values","Keep the courts busy and employ lawyers","Replace the need for elected representatives"],"a":1,"expl":"Our laws are intended to provide order in society and a peaceful way to settle disputes, and to express the values and beliefs of Canadians.","diff":2},{"id":"just-019","chapter":7,"type":"tf","q":"The RCMP serves as the provincial police in Ontario and Quebec.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"False. Ontario and Quebec have their own provincial police forces. The RCMP serves as the provincial police in all provinces and territories except Ontario and Quebec.","diff":3},{"id":"just-020","chapter":7,"type":"mc","q":"In which of these situations does the guide say you can ask the police for help?","opts":["If someone you know has gone missing","If you need legal advice for a contract","If you want to appeal a court decision","If you want to nominate someone for an honour"],"a":0,"expl":"You can ask the police for help in all kinds of situations: an accident, theft, assault, witnessing a crime, or if someone you know has gone missing.","diff":3},{"id":"sym-001","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"When was the new Canadian flag raised for the first time?","opts":["1867","1965","1921","1982"],"a":1,"expl":"A new Canadian flag was raised for the first time in 1965. Red and white had been the national colours of Canada since 1921.","diff":1},{"id":"sym-002","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"What does Canada's national motto, 'A mari usque ad mare,' mean?","opts":["'Peace, order and good government'","'Strong and free'","'From coast to coast'","'From sea to sea'"],"a":3,"expl":"A mari usque ad mare is Latin for 'from sea to sea.' It was adopted along with the coat of arms after the First World War.","diff":1},{"id":"sym-003","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"What is Canada's best-known symbol?","opts":["The beaver","The Crown","The maple leaf","The fleur-de-lys"],"a":2,"expl":"The maple leaf is Canada's best-known symbol. Maple leaves were adopted as a symbol by French Canadians in the 1700s.","diff":1},{"id":"sym-004","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"What is Canada's national winter sport?","opts":["Hockey","Curling","Soccer","Lacrosse"],"a":0,"expl":"Hockey is Canada's most popular spectator sport and is considered to be the national winter sport. Ice hockey was developed in Canada in the 1800s.","diff":1},{"id":"sym-005","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"What is Canada's official summer sport?","opts":["Canadian football","Baseball","Soccer","Lacrosse"],"a":3,"expl":"Lacrosse, an ancient sport first played by Aboriginals, is the official summer sport.","diff":1},{"id":"sym-006","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"Who donated the Stanley Cup, and when?","opts":["Adrienne Clarkson, in 2005","Lord Stanley, the Governor General, in 1892","Queen Victoria, in 1867","Lord Stanley, the Prime Minister, in 1892"],"a":1,"expl":"The National Hockey League plays for the championship Stanley Cup, donated by Lord Stanley, the Governor General, in 1892.","diff":2},{"id":"sym-007","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"What is the Clarkson Cup awarded for?","opts":["Women's hockey","Men's curling","Canadian football","Lacrosse"],"a":0,"expl":"The Clarkson Cup, established in 2005 by Adrienne Clarkson, the 26th Governor General (and the first of Asian origin), is awarded for women's hockey.","diff":3},{"id":"sym-008","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"On which Canadian coin can the beaver be seen?","opts":["The one-dollar coin","The ten-cent coin","The five-cent coin","The twenty-five-cent coin"],"a":2,"expl":"The industrious beaver can be seen on the five-cent coin, on the coats of arms of Saskatchewan and Alberta, and of cities such as Montreal and Toronto.","diff":1},{"id":"sym-009","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"For how long has the Crown been a symbol of the state in Canada?","opts":["100 years","200 years","300 years","400 years"],"a":3,"expl":"The Crown has been a symbol of the state in Canada for 400 years. Canada has been a constitutional monarchy in its own right since Confederation in 1867.","diff":2},{"id":"sym-010","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"Since what year had Queen Elizabeth II been Queen of Canada?","opts":["1945","1952","1967","1982"],"a":1,"expl":"Queen Elizabeth II had been Queen of Canada since 1952; she marked her Golden Jubilee in 2002 and her Diamond Jubilee (60 years as Sovereign) in 2012.","diff":2},{"id":"sym-011","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"Where does the red-white-red pattern of the Canadian flag come from?","opts":["The flag of the Hudson's Bay Company","The Union Jack","The flag of the Royal Military College, Kingston","The Canadian Red Ensign"],"a":2,"expl":"The red-white-red pattern comes from the flag of the Royal Military College, Kingston, founded in 1876.","diff":3},{"id":"sym-012","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"What have been the national colours of Canada since 1921?","opts":["Red and white","Red and blue","Blue and white","Red, white and blue"],"a":0,"expl":"Red and white had been colours of France and England since the Middle Ages and the national colours of Canada since 1921.","diff":1},{"id":"sym-013","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"What is Canada's official Royal Flag?","opts":["The Canadian Red Ensign","The Union Jack","The fleur-de-lys flag","The flag of the Royal Military College"],"a":1,"expl":"The Union Jack is Canada's official Royal Flag. The Canadian Red Ensign served as the Canadian flag for about 100 years.","diff":2},{"id":"sym-014","chapter":8,"type":"tf","q":"The Canadian Red Ensign served as the Canadian flag for about 100 years.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"True. The Canadian Red Ensign served as the Canadian flag for about 100 years, and has been carried officially by veterans since 2005.","diff":2},{"id":"sym-015","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"According to tradition, the fleur-de-lys (lily flower) was adopted by the French king in which year?","opts":["1000","1534","496","1763"],"a":2,"expl":"It is said that the lily flower was adopted by the French king in the year 496. It became the symbol of French royalty for more than 1,000 years.","diff":3},{"id":"sym-016","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"In 1948, Quebec adopted its own flag, based on which symbols?","opts":["The maple leaf and the beaver","The Union Jack and the fleur-de-lys","The Crown and the lily","The Cross and the fleur-de-lys"],"a":3,"expl":"In 1948 Quebec adopted its own flag, based on the Cross and the fleur-de-lys.","diff":2},{"id":"sym-017","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"Canada adopted an official coat of arms and a national motto as an expression of national pride after which event?","opts":["The First World War","Confederation","The Second World War","The War of 1812"],"a":0,"expl":"As an expression of national pride after the First World War, Canada adopted an official coat of arms and a national motto. The arms contain symbols of England, France, Scotland and Ireland as well as red maple leaves.","diff":2},{"id":"sym-018","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"After the fire of 1916, which is the only part of the original Parliament building that remains?","opts":["The Centre Block","The Library","The Peace Tower","The Memorial Chamber"],"a":1,"expl":"The Centre Block was destroyed by an accidental fire in 1916 and rebuilt in 1922. The Library is the only part of the original building remaining.","diff":2},{"id":"sym-019","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"The Peace Tower, completed in 1927, was built in memory of what?","opts":["Confederation","Queen Victoria","The First World War","The Fathers of Confederation"],"a":2,"expl":"The Peace Tower was completed in 1927 in memory of the First World War. The Memorial Chamber within the Tower contains the Books of Remembrance.","diff":2},{"id":"sym-020","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"What is the Victoria Cross (V.C.)?","opts":["The highest honour available to Canadians","An award for women's hockey","A medal for police officers","Canada's oldest civilian award"],"a":0,"expl":"The Victoria Cross is the highest honour available to Canadians, awarded for the most conspicuous bravery, a daring or pre-eminent act of valour or self-sacrifice, or extreme devotion to duty in the presence of the enemy.","diff":1},{"id":"sym-021","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"Who was the first Canadian to be awarded the Victoria Cross?","opts":["Billy Bishop","Filip Konowal","Robert Hampton Gray","Alexander Roberts Dunn"],"a":3,"expl":"Then Lieutenant Alexander Roberts Dunn, born in present-day Toronto, served in the Charge of the Light Brigade at Balaclava (1854) in the Crimean War and was the first Canadian awarded the V.C.","diff":2},{"id":"sym-022","chapter":8,"type":"tf","q":"Able Seaman William Hall of Nova Scotia was the first black man to be awarded the Victoria Cross.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"True. William Hall of Horton, Nova Scotia, whose parents were American slaves, was the first black man awarded the V.C. for his role in the Siege of Lucknow in 1857.","diff":3},{"id":"sym-023","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"Who was the last Canadian to receive the Victoria Cross to date?","opts":["Captain Paul Triquet","Lieutenant Robert Hampton Gray","Corporal Filip Konowal","Captain Billy Bishop"],"a":1,"expl":"Lieutenant Robert Hampton Gray, a navy pilot born in Trail, B.C., was killed while bombing and sinking a Japanese warship in August 1945 and was the last Canadian to receive the V.C. to date.","diff":3},{"id":"sym-024","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"When was 'O Canada' proclaimed as the national anthem?","opts":["1980","1880","1965","1967"],"a":0,"expl":"O Canada was proclaimed as the national anthem in 1980. It was first sung in Québec City in 1880.","diff":1},{"id":"sym-025","chapter":8,"type":"tf","q":"French and English Canadians sing the same words to the national anthem.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"False. French and English Canadians sing different words to the national anthem.","diff":2},{"id":"sym-026","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"What is the Royal Anthem of Canada?","opts":["'O Canada'","'The Maple Leaf Forever'","'God Save the Queen (or King)'","'A Mari Usque Ad Mare'"],"a":2,"expl":"The Royal Anthem of Canada, 'God Save the Queen (or King),' can be played or sung on any occasion when Canadians wish to honour the Sovereign.","diff":1},{"id":"sym-027","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"When is Canada Day celebrated?","opts":["June 24","July 1","April 9","November 11"],"a":1,"expl":"Canada Day is July 1. June 24 is the Fête nationale (Quebec) and April 9 is Vimy Day.","diff":1},{"id":"sym-028","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"When is Remembrance Day?","opts":["November 20","July 1","April 9","November 11"],"a":3,"expl":"Remembrance Day is November 11. November 20 is Sir Wilfrid Laurier Day.","diff":1},{"id":"sym-029","chapter":8,"type":"tf","q":"Hockey has the most registered players of any game in Canada.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"False. Soccer has the most registered players of any game in Canada, although hockey is the most popular spectator sport.","diff":3},{"id":"sym-030","chapter":8,"type":"mc","q":"Canada started its own honours system with the Order of Canada in which year?","opts":["1854","1945","1917","1967"],"a":3,"expl":"After using British honours for many years, Canada started its own honours system with the Order of Canada in 1967, the centennial of Confederation.","diff":2},{"id":"econ-001","chapter":9,"type":"mc","q":"What are the three main types of industries in Canada?","opts":["Tourism, banking and farming industries","Forestry, fishing and mining industries","Service, manufacturing and natural resources industries","Technology, automotive and energy industries"],"a":2,"expl":"Canada's economy includes three main types of industries: service industries, manufacturing industries and natural resources industries.","diff":1},{"id":"econ-002","chapter":9,"type":"mc","q":"What country is Canada's largest international trading partner?","opts":["The United States","Mexico","The United Kingdom","Japan"],"a":0,"expl":"Canada's largest international trading partner is the United States. Canada and the U.S. have the biggest bilateral trading relationship in the world.","diff":1},{"id":"econ-003","chapter":9,"type":"mc","q":"What percentage of working Canadians have jobs in service industries?","opts":["About 25%","About 50%","Less than 10%","More than 75%"],"a":3,"expl":"More than 75% of working Canadians now have jobs in service industries such as transportation, education, health care, construction, banking, communications, retail services, tourism and government.","diff":1},{"id":"econ-004","chapter":9,"type":"mc","q":"In what year did Canada enact free trade with the United States?","opts":["1967","1988","1994","2008"],"a":1,"expl":"In 1988, Canada enacted free trade with the United States. Mexico became a partner in 1994 in the broader North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA).","diff":2},{"id":"econ-005","chapter":9,"type":"mc","q":"When did Mexico become a partner in the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA)?","opts":["1988","1992","2008","1994"],"a":3,"expl":"Mexico became a partner in 1994 in the broader North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA), with over 444 million people and over $1 trillion in merchandise trade in 2008.","diff":2},{"id":"econ-006","chapter":9,"type":"mc","q":"According to the guide, Canada is part of which group of leading industrialized countries?","opts":["The G8","The European Union","The Commonwealth Economic Council","NATO's economic committee"],"a":0,"expl":"Canada has one of the ten largest economies in the world and is part of the G8 group of leading industrialized countries with the United States, Germany, the United Kingdom, Italy, France, Japan and Russia.","diff":2},{"id":"econ-007","chapter":9,"type":"mc","q":"How much of Canada's exports are destined for the United States?","opts":["About one-quarter","About half","Over three-quarters","Nearly all"],"a":2,"expl":"Over three-quarters of Canadian exports are destined for the U.S.A. Canada and the U.S. have the biggest bilateral trading relationship in the world.","diff":2},{"id":"econ-008","chapter":9,"type":"mc","q":"Which of the following are natural resources industries?","opts":["Banking, tourism and government","Forestry, fishing, agriculture, mining and energy","Paper, aerospace and automobiles","Transportation, education and health care"],"a":1,"expl":"Natural resources industries include forestry, fishing, agriculture, mining and energy. They have played an important part in the country's history and development.","diff":1},{"id":"econ-009","chapter":9,"type":"mc","q":"Which of the following is an example of a service industry job area?","opts":["Health care","Aerospace manufacturing","Mining","Forestry"],"a":0,"expl":"Service industries provide jobs in areas like transportation, education, health care, construction, banking, communications, retail services, tourism and government.","diff":1},{"id":"econ-010","chapter":9,"type":"tf","q":"Canada and the United States have the biggest bilateral trading relationship in the world.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"True. Canada enjoys close relations with the United States and each is the other's largest trading partner — the biggest bilateral trading relationship in the world.","diff":2},{"id":"econ-011","chapter":9,"type":"mc","q":"Where is the Peace Arch, which symbolizes the close ties between Canada and the United States, located?","opts":["Niagara Falls, Ontario","Windsor, Ontario","Vancouver, British Columbia","Blaine, in the State of Washington"],"a":3,"expl":"At Blaine in the State of Washington, the Peace Arch symbolizes the close ties and common interests of Canada and the United States.","diff":3},{"id":"econ-012","chapter":9,"type":"mc","q":"Which words are inscribed on the Peace Arch?","opts":["'From sea to sea' and 'the true north strong and free'","'Children of a common mother' and 'brethren dwelling together in unity'","'Peace, order and good government'","'The world's longest undefended border'"],"a":1,"expl":"The Peace Arch is inscribed with the words 'children of a common mother' and 'brethren dwelling together in unity.'","diff":3},{"id":"econ-013","chapter":9,"type":"mc","q":"The Canada-United States border is traditionally known as what?","opts":["The Peace Boundary","The Frontier of Friendship","The world's longest undefended border","The 49th parallel partnership"],"a":2,"expl":"Millions of Canadians and Americans cross every year and in safety what is traditionally known as 'the world's longest undefended border.'","diff":1},{"id":"econ-014","chapter":9,"type":"tf","q":"Canada has one of the ten largest economies in the world.","opts":["True","False"],"a":0,"expl":"True. Today, Canada has one of the ten largest economies in the world and is part of the G8 group of leading industrialized countries.","diff":1},{"id":"econ-015","chapter":9,"type":"mc","q":"According to the guide, NAFTA covered over how many people, with over $1 trillion in merchandise trade in 2008?","opts":["444 million","100 million","250 million","1 billion"],"a":0,"expl":"NAFTA, with Mexico joining in 1994, covered over 444 million people and over $1 trillion in merchandise trade in 2008.","diff":3},{"id":"econ-016","chapter":9,"type":"mc","q":"Which of the following is listed in the guide as a manufactured product?","opts":["Fish","Minerals","Crude oil and natural gas","Aerospace technology"],"a":3,"expl":"Manufactured products include paper, high technology equipment, aerospace technology, automobiles, machinery, food, clothing and many other goods.","diff":2},{"id":"econ-017","chapter":9,"type":"mc","q":"According to the guide, what remains the engine of Canada's economic growth?","opts":["Government spending","Commerce (trade)","Immigration","Natural resources alone"],"a":1,"expl":"Canada has always been a trading nation and commerce remains the engine of economic growth.","diff":2},{"id":"econ-018","chapter":9,"type":"mc","q":"A large percentage of Canada's exports are what?","opts":["High technology equipment","Clothing and textiles","Natural resources commodities","Banking services"],"a":2,"expl":"Today, the economy of many areas of the country still depends on developing natural resources, and a large percentage of Canada's exports are natural resources commodities.","diff":2},{"id":"econ-019","chapter":9,"type":"tf","q":"Mexico entered into free trade with Canada before the United States did.","opts":["True","False"],"a":1,"expl":"False. Canada enacted free trade with the United States in 1988; Mexico became a partner later, in 1994, through NAFTA.","diff":3},{"id":"econ-020","chapter":9,"type":"mc","q":"According to the guide, why is trade with other nations important to Canadians?","opts":["Trade is needed to maintain Canadians' standard of living","Trade is required by the Constitution","Canada has no domestic industries","Trade is needed to fund the monarchy"],"a":0,"expl":"As Canadians, we could not maintain our standard of living without engaging in trade with other nations.","diff":1}];
